reviews.text:
Solid neighborhood brewery that is constantly tweaking and perfecting their beers. Experimenting with a few new brews too. Great that they have some good food here too, wont find that at most breweries and you cant beat the staff. Shoutout to Max. 

Head over for one of their free comedy nights on certain Tuesdays. They do a great job embracing the Winter Hill community, this is just one of the ways they show that.

Beer, dinner and weekend brunch - excellent addition to the neighborhood. Rotating beer list and beers to go for sale. Wide range of beers being brewed on premises, so something for everyone. Brussels Sprouts are incredible.

This is a perfect addition to the neighbourhood. The morning cafe experience rival the "in the square" cafes but with friendlier staff and way more space to stretch out at a lower price point. 

In the evening it can become a hot spot for great craft beer that is brewed on site and pumped right to holding tanks visible from the bar and a kitchen that actively works on their menus. Nothing gets stale here and week over week you have the ability it experience something new, whether it be beer, food, or live entertainment. 

They also offer event venue space.
Good beer selection on tap. The food was very good as well. There were 6 of us and everyone enjoyed their sandwich.

Several varieties of tasty micro brewed-in-house beer, from Belgian to IPA and others.  It's a coffee house before noon, and a pub after.  Small menu with burgers, good sandwiches like Cuban and grilled cheese.

Awesome beer
Buffalo cauliflower - send me the recipe, okay?
AMAZING music

Many moons ago I lived up the the street. If this place was here then, I'd...

WinterHillBrewingCompany.name: Winter Hill Brewing Company
WinterHillBrewingCompany.breweryDescription: The Boston area's first cafe/brewery/restaurant.  5BBL Brewhouse supporting 6 rotating drafts, made in-house, for the house.  Cafe service proudly serving Counter Culture Coffee.  Full Kitchen serving Breakfast, Lunch, and Dinner.

reviews.text: I took a trip to Tree House Brewery and waited on line 50 minutes to get what I came for. The guy ahead of me online said Trillium Brewery Canton was about 50 minutes away and I could score a lot of beer there. After I got a case and 6 beers from Tree House which was their limit I sped off to Canton. The brewery was beautiful and I could taste just about all their offerings in can. I walked out with 6 cases of amazing beer and did not have to wait in a line with hundreds of folks in front of me. In NYC area there are great brewerys but it is difficult to get cans. Trillium always has many varieties of cans. One of the best brewerys in America the beer is exceptional. Worth the drive.

Worst cans of beer I ever had, just plain gross! My wife got two 4 packs of these for me for Christmas because some fool told her how good they were. If you like drinking carbonated grapefruit juice these beers are for you. I tried all four varieties she got and unfortunately dump them all down the sink. Don’t know who they are paying to write these phony reviews but don’t believe them!
We love their beers. At times there is a line but it moves relatively quickly.

One of the best brewery's in Massachusetts, phenomenal IPAs and double IPAs. This location you can only buy beer to go, you can't drink in there but they do have another location that you can drink at in Canton.

For those who love craft beers as Trillium's offerings are among the best in the World. So the Fort Point location is a "beer store" as some like to call it. May I suggest you go to their website before your visit and ask polite, intelligent questions so you don't come away disappointed. I always find the staff very friendly and helpful. Cheers!
I don't consider myself a beer geek. I don't know all the fancy terms for ingredients or how to reconcile things like "mouthfeel", "nose", etc. But I do...

beers.beerDescription: Our flagship American IPA highlights the distinctively aromatic Australian Galaxy hop.  The nose bursts with pine, citrus rind, melon and pineapple. Pronounced flavors of peach, clementine, and tropical fruits are accentuated with moderate bitterness and balanced by a light, biscuity malt character.

Brewed in celebration of the first anniversary of Row 34, our favorite Fort Point oyster bar and craft-beer purveyor, Vicinity highlights a neighborhood collaboration of passion and vision. Appearance is bright and straw-colored. Spicy, earthy aromas of tropical fruit notes abound. Complex flavors of grape juice, light citrus, and lychee emerge on the palate. The pilsner malt provides a cracker crisp malt character and clean, mineral finish.

Our signature American pale ale balances light, crisp, malt character with an abundance of hop-derived aromatics and flavors from the use of Citra and Columbus. The fragrant nose is fresh citrus, tropical fruit, and peach. Bold flavors of pineapple and mango mix with dank notes of zesty citrus and fresh pine needles. With the smooth mouthfeel, gentle bitterness, and dry finish, Fort Point is our standard daily-drinker.

In the spirit of tenacity and camaraderie, Mettle was first created to highlight the milestone of our inaugural year as a brewery. With an intense dual dry-hop treatment of Amarillo and Citra, this medium-bodied Double IPA beckons with aromatics of peach and nectarine. A fusion of grape juice and candied citrus greet the palate while accents of white-wine, grassy hop, and a mellow bitterness reveal themselves on a smooth, dry finish. We continue to brew Mettle in recognition of our devoted following of hopheads that have supported us from the very beginning.

beers.beerName: Galaxy Dry Hopped Fort Point Pale Ale
beers.beerDescription: This version of our signature American pale ale is dry hopped with the pungent Galaxy variety. Enticingly hazy and blonde in appearance with frothy carb, the nose erupts with strong citrus, passion fruit, and pineapple aromatics. Upfront and resinous hop-derived flavors of grapefruit pith, peach, and mango are balanced with a subtle, bready malt character and mild, subdued bitterness.

This popular edition in our “Street” series of India Pale Ales spotlights the remarkably complex Mosaic hop. Melcher Street is hazy, pale orange in appearance and emits aromatic qualities of grapefruit, mild-earthy pine, and mango on the nose. Dank flavors of pine and green hop, along with juicy notes of tropical fruit, melon, and peach, are accentuated with crisp malt character, mild bitterness, and a soft, effervescent mouthfeel.

Our Double Dry Hopped version of Melcher Street; this amped up American IPA features a heavy dose of Mosaic hops. The spicy, resinous, herbal aroma bursts with nuances of tart citrus, tangerine, clementine, and subtle green onion. Bold flavors of under-ripe melon, cantaloupe rind, and pineapple are highlighted with gentle bitterness and delicate, biscuity malt character.

beers.beerName: Double Dry Hopped Congress Street IPA
beers.beerDescription: This amplified version of Congress Street IPA is a focused exhibition of the Galaxy Hop. Milky and yellow-orange in appearance, Double Dry Hopped Congress Street emits fragrant aromatics of mango, pine resin, grapefruit, pineapple, and peach. Explosive flavors of tropical fruit, grassy hop, nectarine, orange rind, and creamy malt inundate the palate with a thick, rich mouthfeel and soft, effervescent carbonation. The finish is full and oily, yet clean, with a light, modest bitterness.

beers.beerName: Mosaic Dry Hopped Fort Point Pale Ale
beers.beerDescription: With this distinctively dank Fort Point variant we feature Mosaic in the dry hop. Pouring a faintly cloudy, canary gold, Mosaic Fort Point emits a fragrant nose of herbal-woodsy hop, passion fruit, and zesty meyer lemon. Thirst quenching flavors of juicy mango, peppy citrus, and earthy hop entwine on the palate with the familiar biscuity mouthfeel, medium body, and bone dry finish of our signature pale ale.

Same base grist as Sleeper Street IPA, but with a double dose of El Dorado in the dry hop. These El Dorado hops impart a powerful aroma of distinctive lime zest, along with notes of grapefruit juice, and a subtle woodsy earthiness.  The taste is bright, floral, and citrusy hop upfront and finishes with candied lime. As with all Trillium “Street” IPA’s, Double Dry Hopped Sleeper Street is dry with medium-light body and a crisp finish.

Our enhanced version of Summer St. IPA features a secondary dry hopping with Simcoe which leads to a fuller mouthfeel, amplified nose, and an intensified depth of grassy, raw hop character. Double Dry Hopped Summer Street is hazy, sunflower gold in appearance with strong aromatics of pine and lemon. Bold flavors of juicy tangerine, pine resin, and green pear dominate the palate with modest bitterness and a dry finish.

Our first IPA brewed and packaged at our new facility in Canton, MA.  El Dorado, Citra, and Columbus hops create a blast of citrus zest, pineapple, wet earth, and woody aromatics.  The flavor brings a pithy bitterness and just a touch of toasted malt.  Medium bodied with a dry, minerally finish.

The first Double IPA produced at our Canton brewery. Featuring four powerful aromatic hop varieties, Galaxy, Mosaic, Nelson Sauvin, and Columbus, Scaled Up emits dank, spicy, aromas that lead into fruity, citrusy flavors of peach and orange on the palate. Lighter in body than most of our other Double IPAs, Scaled Up finishes dry and smooth with a pleasant bitterness.

In another exciting collaborative effort with our neighbors at Barrington Coffee Roasters, we bring you a bold American stout infused with cold-brewed coffee. PM Dawn exhibits an earthy, freshly roasted coffee bean and dark chocolate/mocha nose. The flavor profile consists of vanilla, hot chocolate, and caramel along with rich espresso. With a medium to heavy body, luscious mouthfeel, and light bitterness, PM Dawn is balanced and full, smooth with a drying roast character.

Pot and Kettle with Cold Brew is just one of our many inspired collaborations with Barrington Coffee Roasting Company. With decades of experience hand-selecting and roasting single origin beans from across the world, cold brewed Barrington coffees provide the perfect addition to our signature oatmeal porter. Like a fresh pull of espresso, Coffee Pot & Kettle pours a dark, almost black color with a dense, sepia brown head. Aromas of fresh brewed coffee, nutty cocoa, dark fruits, burnt-caramel, and subtle vanilla waft out of the glass. Moderate in body with medium carbonation; Deep, roasty flavors of cacao, earthy-coffee, mocha, toffee, and dark malt sweep over the palate with an oatmeal-based creaminess and gentle bitterness. To fully explore the wide range of unique aromas and flavors derived from the diverse array of coffees available, we continuously experiment with varying Barrington roasts and blends with each batch of Pot & Kettle with Cold Brew.

This iteration of Dialed In is a fresh, juicy Double IPA intensively dry hopped with Galaxy and El Dorado. Pouring a vibrant, hazy gold; aromas of white wine, tropical fruit, and citrus swirl around the nose. Upfront flavors of grassy hop, lime zest, and pineapple coincide with vinous notes from the mid-fermentation addition of Pinot Gris juice. Soft and creamy with moderate bitterness; Medium-Light bodied with a crisp, dry finish.

UPPER CASE has a delicate, dry pilsner malt character with a smooth, soft, doughy mouthfeel from the raw wheat, oily hop resin which all serves as a canvas for this twice dry hopped 9% double IPA. Overipe mango, pineapple and passion fruit aromas leap out as the beer is poured. The impression of tropical fruit also takes the lead in the flavor which is layered further by white wine, pine resin and grapefruit zest. Hopped primarily with Mosaic with supporting roles played by Galaxy, Citra and Columbus.

Following in the footsteps of our other “Street” IPA’s, Sleeper shares the same base grains while placing the unique El Dorado hop at center stage. Opaque orange-yellow in color with floral aromas of lime zest, grapefruit peel, pine sap, and candied orange. Juicy, hop-driven flavors of bright citrus, melon, and herbal pine are balanced with medium bitterness, fluffy mouthfeel, and dry finish.

As we prepare to open our new facility in Canton, MA, we release our debut brew: Launch Beer. This special brew signifies a collective milestone for the entire Trillium team. Bright in appearance and light in body, this refreshing pale ale bursts with floral hop aromatics of honeysuckle and passion fruit. Featuring Mosaic/Citra in the dry hop and a crisp Pilsner malt backbone, Launch Beer exhibits graceful flavors of stone fruit and citrus with a satisfyingly sessionable bitterness. We raise a glass to you; the devoted community of supporters who have helped us make our dream a reality!

Brewed to test the Mettle of our loyal hopheads, this dank, full-bodied double IPA features intense dual additions of Amarillo and Galaxy. Bright aromatics of peach and nectarine fuse with flavors of tropical fruit and grapefruit on the palate. Accents of pine, resinous hop, and a clean bitterness reveal themselves on a smooth, dry finish.

This iteration of Dialed In is a fresh, juicy Double IPA intensively dry hopped with Galaxy and Citra. Pouring a vibrant, hazy gold; aromas of white wine, tropical fruit, and citrus swirl around the nose. Upfront flavors of grassy hop, orange juice, and pineapple coincide with vinous notes from the mid-fermentation addition of Chardonnay and Gewurztraminer juice. Soft and creamy with moderate bitterness; Medium-Light bodied with a crisp, dry finish.

beers.beerName: Double Dry Hopped A Street IPA
beers.beerDescription: Same base grist as A Street IPA, but with a double dose of Amarillo in the dry hop. These Amarillo hops impart a powerful floral aroma with distinctive notes of citrus zest. The taste is bright, floral, and citrusy upfront, finishing with candied grapefruit and orange. As with all Trillium “Street” IPA’s, Double Dry Hopped A Street is dry with medium-light body and a crisp finish.

This new edition in our “Street” series of India Pale Ales spotlights the remarkably complex Nelson Sauvin hop. Stillings Street is hazy, pale orange in appearance and emits aromatic qualities of kiwi, white grape and lemongrass on the nose. Delicate flavors of citrus zest, pineapple and cantaloupe are accentuated with crisp malt character, mild bitterness, and a soft, effervescent mouthfeel.

Brewed with 30% wheat, this hoppy, golden American ale features Galaxy and Citra in the dry hop. Bright aromatics of overripe peach, orange rind, and green, herbal hops flood the nose while balanced flavors of tropical fruit, citrus, and creamy wheat excite the palate. Refreshingly light bodied with a soft, fluffy mouthfeel, Pier finishes dry with a slightly mineral bitterness.

Secret Stairs is our signature Boston Stout. Bold and balanced; satisfying with a substantial body, but not syrupy or sweet. Roasted malt provides a nutty, earthy backdrop to bitter cocoa and little hints of caramel. Smooth mouthfeel with a drying sensation on the finish. We brew Secret Stairs to highlight the unique physical connection between Summer Street and A Street. We raise a pint of Secret Stairs to The Fort Pointer; the neighborhood's favorite protagonist!

TrilliumBrewingCompany.name: Trillium Brewing Company
TrilliumBrewingCompany.breweryDescription: We are a family owned and operated brewery in the Fort Point Channel neighborhood of Boston, Massachusetts. We created Trillium to realize our dream of bringing creative and flavorful beers to you. These beers are what we envision might have been made today, if a centuries old beer culture had naturally evolved in New England.  To achieve this vision, we stand our craft beers on the shoulders of native ingredients and artisan practices, balancing them with modern-day expertise.

userTips.tip: The 1st brewery to open in Boston proper in decades, Trillium was named 1 of RateBeer's top 10 new breweries for 2013. Tastes, growlers & releases at the taproom; bottles on CBC shelves regularly!

reviews.text: Michelle Braga and Somerville Brewing Company helped with a recent surprise party for my partner. Michelle was quick to respond to my reservation inquiry and was thorough and detailed in explaining the costs and accommodations that were available- even working to be sure that there were a few vegan options for my partner. The party was held in the brewers loft on Ward Street- beer was easy to get at the bar downstairs, food was incredible- a hit with all of our guests, and the staff was super friendly! I would definitely recommend both Michelle and Somerville Brewing Company for your private event.

This place is awesome. Great unique beer, wonderfull staff and the food is amazing, all for an even better price. The pulled pork nachos are the BEST! Love the music too. Must visit when in Boston! I'm most certainly a regular customer from now on.

One of the best small breweries in the Boston area. Their staff is friendly, their beer selection diverse and delicious, and their food is great. While not in the most convenient location, they are well worth the stop.

We (3 of us) visited this evening and met the owners as well as enjoyed the comedy show. The selection and quality of their brews was phenomenal and the food was spectacular. Too notch tap ro. Highly recommend!

You can get nice beers anywhere in breweries and restaurants etc, but I personally think theirs taste distinguished. Now my favorites are newly released my better half (imperial cream ale) and highlander (scotch ale). several sets of samplers are fun to try. Good selections of foods too. Just one thing is that cooking is slow...

Recommend! 
I enjoy just hanging here getting silly with my friends. I had to come a few times in order to decide - 3 or 4 stars? The food can be very hit...

beers.beerDescription: Flagraiser IPA is a big, hoppy tribute to the unfurling of the Grand Union flag atop Prospect Hill in Somerville, MA on January 1, 1776. This ale celebrates our passion for hop aroma and flavor balanced with just the right amount of malt. Huge aroma and resin-y flavors from the elusive Galaxy hops are the signature of this beer. Built on a solid base of pale malts, this double IPA makes generous use of hops from Columbus, Crystal and Galaxy with the Galaxy hops taking the lead during ten days of aggressive dry-hopping.

A refreshingly tart and crisp hefeweizen brewed with local MA wildflower honey, orange peel and coriander, and fermented with the juice from over 1,000 blood oranges. It’s a cloudy, yet effervescent beer, with lingering banana and citrus notes balanced against a healthy wheat backbone and hoppy finish from Mt. Hood and Crystal hops.

Rich black porter with a unique blend of chocolate, coffee, roasted and nutty flavors. Brewed with cocoa powder and conditioned with cacao nibs from Taza Chocolate. Bold flavors from the cacao nibs and black malts are balanced with a special blend of pale malts, oats and wheat to produce a lush and lingering mouthfeel.

A smooth and alluring Belgian golden ale with complex fruity pineapple flavors set against a spicy finish. Dried jasmine flowers added in the boil work with a higher alcohol level to augment Belgian pilsen, caramel and honey malts. Hop character include Chinook and Moteuka hops grown in New Zealand.

An autumn brown ale with distinctive toasty flavors from an assortment of roasted malts and grains. As a seasonal, fall beer, its nutty characteristics offer a great companion to colder climate cuisine. A bright hop finish from Cascade and Fuggles balance the toasted grain notes to create a new expression of autumn brown ales.

It wasn't always his temperament, but they were the ones ... the ones that went looking for him after all. Today is a new day. Lobstah Killah Imperial Red Ale is a special blend of Maris Otter and other malts balance a resiny mix of Columbus, Cascade and Simcoe hops. Our hoppy imperial red ale is the beer of choice for imperial decisions.

LIMITED SEASONAL RELEASE! It's often said there is a better half responsible for making us whole, and so goes the inspiration for this ale. One half of the fermentation is cold lagered and the remaining half is finished as a warm ale fermentation. The result is a smooth and composed imperial cream ale well suited for contemplation.
A LIMITED IPA project from Slumbrew Luma Luma is derived from a complex combination of malts, yeasts and hops so this multilayered IPA weighs in at 7.3% abv.

How many hops are enough for an IPA? We think it's not just quantity, but the blend of varieties as we strive for hoppy delusions in this extremely limited release IPA for the lover of all things humulus lupulus. This beer is light golden in color from pilsner and caramel malts, with a cloudy haze from the addition of wheat. It's an unfiltered compilation of Nugget, Columbus, Zythos, Simcoe and a new experimental hop from the Pacific-Northwest referenced only by HBC-342.
Gose with hibiscus

Today, we breathe in deeply. Fresh air and the aromatic essence of Calypso, Ella and Pacific Jade hops fill the air and lighten our hearts while this golden ale lightens our mood. Today is an Island Day. Keep cold, enjoy now for today is the day. Serve at 45º - 50º F

You could gift this bottle as a reflection of your fine craft beer taste, drink it now to ease your holiday tension or cellar for the long winter ahead. For our first year of our Yankee Swap beer series, we selected rum barrels from our friends at Turkey Shore Distilleries and dark maple syrup from North Hadley Sugar Shack. This Strong Ale is a big beer with hints of maple and complex notes of oak and rum from the Old Ipswich rum barrels.
Porter Aged on Coffee and Toasted Coconut

Summertime is for love, laughter and play, not envy. Never mind those luscious, long climbing vines of spicy, herbal hop cones over there. Sure there is a time for IPA, but today we will be content with smooth and floral Saison. Be happy. Brewed with Belgian aromatic malts, wheat and noble hops. Serve in a goblet or snifter at 45F for optimal enjoyment.
White IPA with mosaic hops

Hopheads go to great extremes in their lupulin quests. It's a worthy endeavor, but fraught with falling across the event horizon in a hoppy stupor. With swirling flavors from both dark malts and the crisp body from pilsner grains, our limited release black IPA will take you to the center of a hop explosion and back, without all the crushing gravity.

Meet Creep. Ever wonder who's responsible for seasonal beers popping up before their time? SeasonALE Creep thinks it's funny to release a pumpkin beer in August or a holiday ale in September. He's a greedy little character, robbing us of time and demanding we move on too soon. We'd be down on Creep, except he brought this refreshing Belgian-style saison brewed with light pilsner malts, wheat and galaxy hops.

Garde La Pêche is refreshingly tart from the first sip with a round mouthfeel and increasing sweetness, many sun-ripened bushels of peaches per batch. A bright and refreshing pairing for a fine summer day.

beers.beerName: Sittin' On Hop Of The World
beers.beerDescription: "You don’t like my peaches, don’t shake my tree. Get out of my orchard, let my peaches be." Our white IPA is a hybrid ale brewed with wheat malts and fermented with fresh peach puree. The aromatic essence of peach flavors combines with a world of hoppy goodness from Galena, Amarillo and Citra hops.
This IPA features Galaxy hops as the star of the show, with a bright citrus aroma giving way to a crisp finish.

Limited vertical series 
Belgian Quad aged in oak rum barrels.
Our first gourdeous new Pumpkin Beer called Slumkin Pumpkin.
Strawberry wheat
Belgian Ale brewed with Cap'n Crunchberries
Nitro Stout

SomervilleBrewingCompany.name: Somerville Brewing Company (Slumbrew)
SomervilleBrewingCompany.breweryDescription: Make good liquids, make good friends. Since its inception in 2011, the brewery has expanded distribution into six states, achieved annual production of over 2,000 barrels of beer and grown from 2 employees to over 35. The recent addition of two retail destinations to enjoy its core brand of Slumbrew beer with innovative food offerings, along with its own Somerville brewery location are milestones along an exciting path of growth. There are two locations in Somerville MA: The Brewery + Taproom at 15 Ward Street and an outdoor beer garden at Assembly Row.

userTips.tip: Great brews, friendly employees, Cartoon Network was on TV during our visit. Make your own flight - we picked 8 beers for ours.

reviews.text: Great local brewery. They have a very large selection of beers of different types (including less common varieties such as sours). The food is also excellent, and the portions sizes are adequate for an adult. The prices are reasonable for a meal in Cambridge.

Great place to go if you want solid, well-crafted, and bold American food. The atmosphere and service were excellent as well. I ordered a BBQ Burger (they perfectly cooked it rare) and my wife had the Pickle Brined Fried Hot Chicken (it was AMAZING!! Definite recommendation!). Also, their brewed beers are nice. Personally, I enjoyed their Chocolate Babka Stout and my wife really loved The Fog that Surrounds. 

Prices are reasonable and the people are cool. This really is a great place to visit and we look forward to experiencing more of their menu.

Check out this restaurant!

I went there for the Boston Chefs Hunger Brunch, a brunch whose proceeds went to the Greater Boston Food Bank.  There was a special menu that you could choose from.  I chose the banana bread french toast sticks and the bagel sandwich with cheese, pepper jelly and watercress and both dishes were delicious. Although those specific items are not on the regular menu, trying them gave me a taste of what the restaurant has to offer and makes me want to go back.

We were meeting up with a group of old college friends who hadn't gotten together in 15+ years.  We wanted a spot in the Kendall Square area where we could not only get great food & drink, but also have a quiet enough environment to hear each other and catch up (boy, do we sound old!!).  We made reservations at CBC and couldn't have been more thrilled.  While most other nights we love sitting at the bar in the thick of things (and even on a Sunday evening the bar was hopping), we were seated with a few other parties in a calmer back room where the volume was perfect.  Service was attentive, the food and beer were excellent, and we couldn't have asked for more!  Definitely recommended whether you're seeking a loud and crazy night or a more calm & quiet experience.

We have a family tradition to come here the day after Christmas. I always loved the tradition when I was underage for the food, and now I'm of age and love it for the beer. Staff is extremely nice, food is tasty, beer is tasty. Check this place out.

Great local brew house, with a good selection of beers and American bites. 

CBC is a fairly large restaurant with an outdoor portion, so you can usually...

beers.beerDescription: This American-style IPA stands head and shoulders above its hoppy brethren, blending pale and honey malts to balance the palate without interfering in your herbal reverie, and creating a new American classic.

Brewed with Pilsner, CaraVienne, and Rye malts, plus Magnum and Spalter hops.  But the driving force behind this beer is the contribution from whole Black, Green, White, and Pink peppercorns. Added to the brewkettle, these four fab peppercorns harmonize with spicy hops while the malted rye and our Belgian yeast hold down the backbeat.

Pilsner malt and flaked rice provide sweet cereal grain notes while German and Czech hops add spiciness and a balanced bitterness to the finish. Cold fermented and aged with a German lager yeast, the palate is clean with a snappy finish.

CBC’s Great Pumpkin Ale is brewed with over 150 pounds of fresh, locally grown, organic sugar pumpkins in each batch, and it has an appropriately distinct orange hue. The subtle fresh pumpkin flavor is enhanced by the addition of a touch of traditional autumn spices, and is guaranteed to please even the most finicky of harvest-time ale fanatics. Come raise a glass in honor of the Great Pumpkin!

Well balanced, medium-bodied, with a deep amber-red color, this beer's complex palate covers all the bases. A malty caramel sweetness is followed by notes of chocolate and a dry, slightly roasty finish, complemented by a touch of fruity, spicy hops.

Barley, wheat, rye and oats combine with hops and citrus peel in this new American saison. Created by men and women who have forged their own paths to craft your beer, here’s a liquid reward for heroic people everywhere who take pride in an honest day’s work.
Big and bold, our Pale Ale distinguishes itself by its huge, fresh hop aroma and flavor. A combination of Cascade and Centennial hops gives this beer its nectarious flavor.

You want an IPA, you’ve got one, but with a twist! “Spring Training” breezes in like a breath of fresh air, ready to awaken your senses from a long, cold winter. Crafted primarily of New England-grown pale malts, the recipe also incorporates Belgian carapils and wheat malts to contribute to the beer’s complex body and straw-golden color. Ahtanum and Palisades hops, both relative newcomers on the hop varietal scene, were chosen for their essence of wildflowers and freshly-cut grass, evocative of springtime breezes. This is in contrast to the piney, earthy and resiny characteristics of most IPAs. In addition to extensive kettle hopping the beer is dry-hopped with even Ahtanums to satisfy your hop-craving.

Deep and dark, full-bodied and robust, our Porter is crammed full of rich, roasted malt character. With underlying notes of fruitness, caramel and toffee, it finishes
with a strong hop presence.
CBC's winter seasonal I.P.A.

THE CROWD GOES WILD! A smooth bass line of roasted notes establishes the deep end beneath arpeggios of complex chocolate malt, while power chords of caramelized grain open up to an extended malty jam. Black barley teases treacle character and wades into a velvety sea of oak-derived vanilla and toasted coconut tones. Sustained improvisation of fruitiness modulates to an intense finale, and encores with a rich, espresso-roasted reprise, a capella.
With elder flowers and dry hopped with Nelson Sauvin.

The best day of the year comes once every summer when the Brew Crew and friends travel to Westport on Massachusetts’ Atlantic Coast to pick fresh heather flowers. After a long day of toiling in the sun, we hustle home and add them to the kettle to create our world famous Heather Ale.Brewed with imported Scottish floor-malted barley, fresh hand-harvested heather flowers are added to the kettle during the boil along with sweet gale and lavender, with a further addition of fresh heather and yarrow to the conditioning tanks.
Our 26th Anniversary Beer — Barrel fermented wild ale w/ oats, raw wheat and buckwheat. Floral and fruity, notes of pineapple and guava, clean cereal grains, super dry finish.

Every batch of CBC HefeWeizen is brewed with Massachusetts-grown organic wheat, which has been malted for us by our friends in Hadley, MA at Valley Malt. By the way, Weisse (white) and Weizen (wheat) are two interchangeable terms in regards to naming this style, and the words mit hefe (with yeast) indicate that this is an unfiltered beer.

So enjoy your summer with a cold CBC HefeWeizen, and show your support for sustainable, organic farms and small businesses in Massachusetts!

Our grisette is a hazy, bright gold from a complex grist of organic pilsner and wheat malts, plus organic oats, rye, and buckwheat. Subtly hopped with Spalt and Hallertauer hops which contribute balance and a hint of floral character, though the grains are really on display. Tart fruity, spicy grain flavors come from the rye and buckwheat and are bolstered by spice notes and hints of citrus from a special guest yeast strain, that of the famous Brasserie d’Achouffe.

A session beer with Belgian ancestry, this seemingly simple biére de table is surprisingly complex. Served in a traditional tulip glass to emphasize the glowing effervescence and special nature of this delightful little beer

Cerise Cassée is a complex beer in both process and palate. Multiple fermentations begin in stainless steel with our house ale yeast, then spontaneous refermentation and aging along with 300 pounds of sour cherries takes place in the infamous CBC barrel cellar.

An arquebus was a primitive firearm which came into use in the 15th Century, and was a predecessor to the musket and rifle. A smoothbore with a flared muzzle, similar but more refined and accurate than its predecessor the Blunderbuss (ah, there’s the thematic association, Blunderbuss being our winter barleywine…)

Brewed in the tradition of the fresh, blond ales of Cologne, Germany, our Golden ale is light in body, crisp and very refreshing. Its soft malt flavor is balanced by delicate, spicy hop flavors and finishes.

“The Cure” is a pale ale brewed with barley, oats, and wheat. It focuses on the prominent notes of herbs, stone fruit, green apple, pine, tropical mango and floral character, and tangerine and lime citrus character, all provided by the hops.
Berlin-Style Wheat Beer. Light, refreshing, tart with lactobacillus

CambridgeBrewingCompany.name: Cambridge Brewing Company
CambridgeBrewingCompany.breweryDescription: Established in 1989, Cambridge Brewing Company is the oldest brewpub in the greater Boston area serving fresh handcrafted beer and food made with local ingredients.

userTips.tip: An extraordinarily experimental local brew pub. Short rib poutine and a pizza topped with local foraged mushrooms are different from the usual pub fare, and an outdoor patio offers coveted seats.
Mark your calendar for CBC Pumpkin Fest around Halloween. It's an amazing selection of over 40 different pumpkin beers. Spectacular event!
Do Not bring toddlers and kids - seriously, WTF, this is a brew pub - come for the bier and la dolce vita
The Charles River Porter here is simply the best porter ever!
Tower of Beer.  Don't ask why, just try!

reviews.text: Not satisfied with the quality of staff who were too busy concerning themselves with conforming to strict liquor laws rather than accepting a valid ID, albeit not a passport, and a valid secondary ID, over providing good service. I understand they have to follow the laws, but as a Boston native who has taken international friends to various establishments around Boston , I am frankly shocked and appalled of finding an institution that conforms to the letter of the law rather than the spirit of the law. But whatever. I'm not coming back. Make sure you have a passport when you get here if you're not American
Great beer and amazing pop up foods. Best thing; free brewery tour with laughter 😀😀😀. Thank you for great experience every visit ❤️❤️❤️

Very good different flavored beers my favorite is to stay out which is very tasty. The different food trucks they have in give a variety of Boston flavored food. Also free pizza Monday is a great touch keep up the good work guys
Great local brewery with lots of options on the tap list. If you live in Dorchester this is a must go to place.

Tasty beers on tap, all brewed in Dorchester MA. 

Dot Brewing offers their own recipes, as well as also serving pours of their contract beers, all brewed in house. Backlash, Omnipollo, Evil Twin, and Exhibit A often turn up. Many styles available, and I've enjoyed every beer ive tried there. 

A true gem for Dorchester.
Was heading out of Boston in a few hours and was looking for quick local brewery to try. The place opened before noon, had really good beer, and had a bar...

beers.beerDescription: A pale, hoppy ale brewed with an over abundance of hops, 3 lbs per barrel of American hops (Citra, Mosaic,El Dorado) in the whirlpool and 3 lbs per barrel for dry hopping (2/3rd Hallertauer Tradition and 1/3 Citra).  5.5% ABV

Dark brown with Chestnut highlights. Roasted coffee and chocolate aroma. Super smooth, complex palate from de-bittered dark malts, German hops, and our house lager yeast. Originally brewed in the Baltic region and rooted in British Porter tradition, taking cues from Russian Imperial Stout. Warming alcohol with a bold, lingering finish. 7.4 ABV

A not very bitter beer at all, the ESB has a smooth, malty initial mouthful that transitions to a marmalade like fruitiness from the East Kent Goldings hop variety. Toffee and light dried fruit notes.
Piney, resinous & brilliant.  Moderate bitterness from this brownish red IPA is perfect for post-summer porch sitting.

Festivus for the rest of us! A German Starkbier traditionally brewed for the holidays. Dominant malt flavors with some candied fruit notes. Noticeable alcohol. The German equivalent of English Barleywine. Perfect for feats of strength and airing of grievances!

Served on Nitro.  Bittered with Chinook hops and fermented with our British yeast strain, this stout has lots of roasted barley, creating it’s deep brown color and smoky, cocoa notes. Embrace the stout! ABV 5%
Fully bright and deep golden fall classic. Brewed with Vienna and Pilsner malts with a malty sweetness.
Berliner Weisse, the “people’s champagne”. Tart and crisp.  Highly effervescent with sparkling wine notes and a crackery malt finish. Try with raspberry or woodruff syrup for a fun addition.
Solid malt with hard candy sweetness. Big grapefruit notes, hints of lime and tropics from Citra kettle and dry hopping. Tightly wound with dark super fruit character from our Belgian yeast.
It’s the beer for it’s true time and place, it just fits right there. Imperial IPA brewed with Golden Promise & Citra (5# per BBL). Citrusy and malty w/ notes of orange and grapefruit. ABV 9.1%
A hazy yellow Saison with a bright white foam cap. Effervescent, earthy, bready aroma and flavor throughout with a dry spicy finish. 4.7% ABV
A traditional German smoked lager (Rauchbier), with 33% Beechwood smoked malt. Sweet doughy malt finish with subtle smoke throughout. 6.5% ABV
Doppel Berliner Weisse with pear. Clean ale yeast. Slightly tart, with a crackery wheat snap. 7% ABV.
This rusty, reddish brown beer has a lasting tan foam with a sweet, stone fruit aroma and flavor. You'll taste a mild malt presence with nutty spice and caramel notes. Clocks in at 6.9% ABV.
Unfiltered and bursting with grassy herbal notes form German Magnum and Czech Saaz hops. Refreshing bitterness gives way to a crisp malt finish. ABV 5.7%
Inspired by Girl Scout cookies and menthols, this dry stout was aged on cocoa nibs for subtle chocolate flavor and aroma. Mint leaves were added for a fresh, clean finish. Mint dude. 5% ABV

This Belgian Tripel is dense with lacey foam atop a golden orange hue. It is highly carbonated, with notes of spice, earth and bread with big Belgian yeast notes of white pepper and cloves. Dry malt and moderate bitterness give way to a sneaking sweetness of alcohol. 9.5% ABV

A Brown Porter aged on Cocoa Nibs. Sweet chocolate syrup aroma with roast coffee notes. Fairly light bodied, with a rich, lingering finish of semi-sweet chocolate and roasted malt flavors. ABV: 5.3% B_ Su_e _o dri_k y_ur O_a_tin_!

Perfect golden straw color, our version of the Pilsner
is bursting with grassy herbal notes from Noble
German Hallertauer and Czech Saaz hops. Refreshing bitterness gives way to a crisp malt finish.

DorchesterBrewingCompany.name: Dorchester Brewing Co.
DorchesterBrewingCompany.breweryDescription:
Dorchester Brewing Company is a partner brewing facility in Boston, MA. When you visit our brewery, you’ll enjoy more than your typical tasting room. Our 20 line tap system is filled with a wide variety of fresh craft beer including our house beers, local brewing partners and regional collaborators on tap for all to consume and taste. Fresh, new, innovative, trendy beers. Try a tasting flight or full pours and grab fresh beer to go!

Our Tap Room is welcome to anyone that wants to visit – beer nerds, beer novices, families, children, people who would rather work here enjoying some beers then at their home offices! We’ve got plenty of games for all to enjoy, wi-fi, food trucks, as well as merchandise and fresh beer to go. We look forward to sharing our love of beer with everyone!

www.dorchesterbrewing.com

reviews.text: We never know what we are going to find when we walk into Lamplighter.  If you are a true beer person this is the best brewery in Boston.  Their rotation is always clever and every time they take off one of my favorite beers it seems the replacement is even better.  I love how they experiment with new ingredients and new techniques yet always stay true to brewing great beer.  You will not find a better staff...nothing is a problem for any of their employees.

Love the vibe of this small brewery. It’s a coffee shop by morning, and relaxed brewery scene by mid-afternoon/evening (although you can still order coffee with your beer). It is a smaller place so can get crowded on the weekends, but during the week and earlier hours, it’s a great place to get some work done or catch up with friends. I love to come here and try their new beers and play one of their many board games. One of my favorites in Boston!

Lamplighter is a small sized brewery. It's a pretty happening place, so you may need to expect a line, though modest on the weekends. They host food vendors as well on some nights making it a food place to grab a beer or two and a bite to eat. 

Solid beer selection that's pretty smooth. Mostly, they feature sours and of course an IPA or 3.

Good but not great beer and, more importantly, too crowded to enjoy the space. I would recommend improving queuing and prompt service while discouraging individual customers from camping to study, read, etc. in prime spaces. The vibe is cool but the logistical challenge definitely distracts from the experience.

Lots of great beers with good service to boot. Expect a line on weekends, but you usually can skip it if you're just going in to buy cans and crowlers.  The back room recently opened and increased the capacity twofold, and it has a nice skylight so that some natural light floods in during the day. The front room has large windows as well.
If this had been around in my "going out" hayday, I would have LOVED it here.  We came in on a Saturday night and got two seats at the bar.  I got their...

beers.beerDescription: A New England-style IPA brewed with Mosaic, Citra, Columbus. Birds has become a staple of our roster because of its fruit-forward hop flavors of dank citrus and passionfruit, coupled with a smooth finish. The beer takes its name from the Phish cult-classic of the same name. Tasting Notes: Spruce, Lemongrass, Blueberry

A dangerously drinkable New England-style double IPA brewed with Citra, Amarillo, and Idaho 7. This beer is a veritable juice bomb, boasting huge hop flavors of mango, melon, and ripe fruit. Kick back and hop to it! Tasting notes: Tropical, Hop Candy, Ripe Mango

An IPA brewed with Summit, Simcoe, and Amarillo. Honeydew hits the palate first, followed by a bit of bitterness and a blast of hop flavor. Think pink-colored Starburst. Named in honor of the Bowie fan in all of us, with a slight nod to a special heroine from Star Wars. Tasting Notes: Citrus, Pine, zest

Our house porter brewed with a variety of black, crystal, and English malts. With a smooth, roasty body and a ton of toffee and chocolate goodness, this beer is bound to get you howling. Werewolves is particularly drinkable for its style, keeping things more tame than an all-out boozy or syrupy porter. Named after Warren Zevon’s classic ballad, “Werewolves Of London.” Awooooo! Tasting Notes: Robust Coffee, Treacle, Dark Fruit

An oat IPA brewed with El Dorado and Centennial. Lucid leans more West Coast than East, sporting pine and citrus flavors that linger on the palate thanks to the addition of body-boosting oats. This beer takes its name from a spaceship in The Culture series. Tasting Notes: Orange, Resin, Citrus Zest

A New England-style pale ale brewed with Citra and Hull Melon. This beer is apricot- and melon-forward, with a balanced malt profile to boot. Those light and hoppy flavors converge for one drinkable, out-of-this-world crusher. Named after a spaceship in The Culture series. Tasting Notes: Kiwi, Melon, Pine
An approachable Gose, mildly salted and tart. A great sipper with lemony tartness, fruity coriander, and notes of crisp, salty ocean air.

Ground Control? This is Major Tom, our New England-style IPA brewed 100% with Galaxy. This Bowie-inspired beer boasts bold flavors of passionfruit and mango, alongside a creamy mouthfeel and smooth finish. Just don’t forget your protein pills and helmet. Tasting Notes: Peach, Passionfruit, Mango

A British pale ale infused with coffee from our friends at Longfellows. A light and fruity Ethiopian roast is added at the end of the brewing process to preserve as much coffee flavor as possible. The finished beer is made up of about 10% coffee. That slight addition gives this beer just enough of a coffee kick to accentuate its mild flavors of malt, pecan, and biscuit. Tasting Notes: Toffee, Toasted Pecan, Bright

An IPA brewed with Amarillo, El Dorado, and 240 pounds of raw honey. While the addition of that much honey may scream sweet, this beer is quite balanced. Citrusy and floral hop notes lead to a slightly dry finish, with a touch of lingering sweetness. In other words, this beer is all of your hop and honeycomb-dipped dreams in liquid form. Named after our unofficial brewhouse anthem, “Lawyers, Guns, and Money” by Warren Zevon. Tasting Notes: Citrus, Floral, Honey

A 100% Brett-fermented IPA hopped with Amarillo and El Dorado. Easy Tiger possesses a more hop-forward profile than our other Brett-based offerings: complex, fruity, tropical flavors of grilled pineapple and black pepper quickly combine with earthy, dank flavors from the wild yeast. The beer takes it name from a craft beer bar in Austin, Texas, where the vision for Lamplighter’s funky and tasty beers was first realized. Welcome to the jungle…Tasting Notes: Mango, Pineapple, Savory

A wheat ale brewed with chamomile and honey. Light and smooth, this beer makes it easy to hit cruise control for the night. Despite the addition of syrupy raw honey to the brew, Group Theory has a lovely, dry finish as a result of the fermentation of its simple sugars. It takes its name from a central concept of abstract algebra, which pays homage to both the math background of one of our co-founders, and to our brewery name (which is partially a math reference itself). Tasting Notes: Honey, Chamomile, Grain

beers.beerName: So Much For Subtlety with Citra
beers.beerDescription: Our rotating double IPA series. Each batch of this hoppy beer highlights a different hop addition, presenting everchanging hop flavors atop the same base beer. Another beer named after a spaceship in The Culture series. This time with Citra.

A 100% Brett IPA brewed with Sorachi Ace and Citra hops. This is the second pitch of our Easy Tiger brett yeast. While Easy Tiger is more fruit-forward, Lion Eyes is fermented at a cooler temperature, which restricts the production of the those fruity and funky flavors. Instead, this beer finishes with a dry, champagne-y taste that’s more expected from a Brett-fermented beer. Expect some slightly subdued funk, a bit of apple and pear flavor, and an effervescent finish. Welcome to the jungle...Tasting Notes: Hay, Dry, Funky
Our rotating fruited sour series. Each batch of this beer highlights a different fruit addition, bolstered by a clean and tart kettle-soured base beer.

beers.beerName: So Much For Subtlety with El Dorado
beers.beerDescription: Our rotating double IPA series. Each batch of this hoppy beer highlights a different hop addition, presenting everchanging hop flavors atop the same base beer. Another beer named after a spaceship in The Culture series. This time with El Dorado.

Double Belgian-style Witbier brewed with lavender, coriander, orange peel, and peppercorn. This witbier plays homage to a traditional style, but with our twist of adding a bit of lavender in. The addition of wheat in the grain bill give this beer a silky smooth mouthfeel, complemented by tangy flavors of spice and Belgian phenols. Lighters up! Tasting Notes: Spice, Lavender, Pepper

Christmas, spice, and everything nice! Our holiday Belgian strong ale is brewed in observance of the winter season, with massive flavors of malt, brown sugar, and chocolate-covered cherry. Cozy up, take a long sip, and let this red-hued delight bring some color to your night. Tasting Notes: Plum, Cherry, Nutmeg

A session wheat IPA brewed with Hallertau Blanc hops. Soft yet punchy flavors of white grape, peach, and pear help ease the palate into a wheaty, full-bodied finish. This beer’s low alcohol content classifies it as a session beer, which simply means you can put a few back in one sitting without feeling like you got run over by a train the next day. At one time, a Watchman was in charge of lighting lamps around town and keeping guard over the town until morning. We felt the name and occupation suited this beer and its drinkability. Tasting Notes: Peach, Gooseberry, White Grape

beers.beerName: Sound And Vision With Tart Cherries
beers.beerDescription: Our rotating fruited sour series. Each batch of this beer highlights a different fruit addition, bolstered by a clean and tart kettle-soured base beer.

Our rotating double IPA series. Each batch of this hoppy beer highlights a different hop addition, presenting everchanging hop flavors atop the same base beer. Another beer named after a spaceship in The Culture series. This time with Centennial

An imperial stout brewed with bourbon Madagascar vanilla beans and over 200 pounds of Vermont maple syrup. If you’re looking for a festive fall beer to welcome in the colder months, look no further: Decadent and rich flavors of vanilla, espresso, and chocolate cake envelop the tongue at first sip. As this beer warms, more complex flavors of black coffee, roasted marshmallow, and molasses will start to surface. Pairs well with chilly fall nights, bonfires, and worn flannel. Tasting Notes: Chocolate Cake, Espresso, Creamy Vanilla
IPA brewed with juice from Satsuma mandarins and dry hopped with loads of Citra and Amarillo

Our true-to-style Belgian blond ale highlights the lightly spicy phenolic character of its yeast, tempered by a gentle pilsner malt profile. This beer is a light sipper, with notes of honeysuckle, pepper, and clove. A lumen is a physical unit of "luminous flux,” or a measure of the visible light emitted by a source. Tack on this beer’s bright and luminous appearance and the name came easy. Tasting notes: Honey, Pepper, Calendula

A smooth and spicy dark saison. Think of this beer as a cross between a brown ale and a true-to-style saison. Here, dark malts and a punch of toffee lead to an effervescent and zesty finish from the Belgian yeast. Despite the style, this beer stays mild enough to entrance more discerning drinkers. Cross over responsibly. Tasting Notes: Malty, Toffee, Spicy

LamplighterBrewing.name: Lamplighter Brewing Co.
LamplighterBrewing.breweryDescription: Our goal is to make beer that you’ve never had anywhere else (or at least that you can't find very easily), but beer that is still drinkable and enjoyable. We want to use tradition as a launching point, and add complexity and depth with our choice of yeast and ingredients. Expect to see a lot of Brettanomyces fermentations, a lot of sour, a lot of funk, and a lot of fun. We hope when you see the name Lamplighter on a menu or label, you’ll have a good idea that you’re in for something creative and delicious.

reviews.text: Huge beer selection. Everything is okay. I feel like every bar around a stadium caters to a certain crowd, and maybe I need to go in with a few more drinks to catch up to everyone's level.
Said was open but door was locked w/o any notice of a private event going on. EDIT: appreciate the response from the owner have updated review to reflect experience at later date.

The food was okay. They never brought out an entree we ordered. The check was wrong when they brought it out (extra food listed and drinks not listed). It took 20 minutes from the time we asked for the check until the time we received it. After 15 minutes of waiting for a server to come get the check, I took my check to a random server and asked to close out. The food was okay, but absolutely nothing was good enough to make up for the abysmal service.
Great place. Great beer and great staff!
Don't order the nachos. They're disgusting and I'm pretty sure they caused food poisoning for some of my friends. Disappointing.
Perfect location if you are going to a Red Sox game or just visiting Fenway for a tour. I was honestly not expecting their beer to be that good, but I left...

Honoring the 2004 Red Sox.  Ruby-colored ale modeled after the pre-prohibition red beers of 1918.
Oatmeal Milk Stout. Real cookies in the mash. Conditioned on vanilla beans and cocoa nibs.

Belgian Christmas Quad brewed with cherries and brown sugar.

The sour cream and chive fries are incredible here! You can get them as a side with a sandwich or burger if you ask!

reviews.text:
Best brewery in the Boston area. Extremely impressive tap list that is constantly rotating and being experimented with. The Santilli IPA is a great staple of theirs. 

Be sure to check out the patio if its nice out and order from the local food truck. Can also BYO food. Ample parking but does get crowded.
Loved it. Great beers, lot of choice on the tap, and a lot more room than in many other breweries. It was still crowded, but hey, with such good beers that's to be expected.

One of the best breweries in Boston! Somewhat of a trek from downtown, but the beer and vibe is worth it. Bartenders were extremely helpful and knowledge. Be sure to check out the rotating food truck as well!

Love this place! It's the perfect place to unwind and enjoy some really nice beers. The neighborhood was pretty dead until these guys showed up and it goes to show how amazing the beer is. I live near by, but I never get bored to the place since they constantly rotate their brews. A must visit!
Amazing microbrewery. Great atmosphere, even better beer. Play games, order food and have it delivered, try flights, buy pints and take some bottles or cans home. Never disappointed.
The first time I went here was during the summer when they were having a food truck festival at the area. It was too busy at the time so my friends and I...

Bronze Medal Winner in the 2016 World Beer Cup American IPA category, Santilli is a smooth-sipping IPA with massive hop profile. It is crisp, tropical and delicious.
A bright, beautiful hop-bomb. It has a simple, clean malt bill that allows its refreshing blend of citrusy hops to burst through; named after our address at 87 Santilli Highway in Everett
Awake is a robust, lively porter for the senses. Its nose of toffee and cacao leads into rich flavors of coffee roast and baker's chocolate. It finishes bitter with a hint of sweetness

Rye ale with agave nectar and habanero peppers. NightShiftBrewing.name: Night Shift Brewing
NightShiftBrewing.breweryDescription: Night Shift Brewing was founded in 2012 by a trio of friends with a shared passion for nocturnal homebrewing. Through culinary inspiration and determined innovation, we aim to create memorable craft beers that offer a wide array of unique, complex flavors.

userTips.tip: If you like beer, you'll LOVE Night Shift. The area is a little sketchy, but once you're inside, it's a beer lovers paradise. Try the Rose. Amazing.
Fantastic brewery with a constantly changing tap list of their own craft beers. Become a barrel society member you won't regret it.
They are totally cool with you bringing your own food. Bread and cheese goes great with beer!
The people who work here are awesome. Great place!
Some of the most unique beers I've ever tasted - choose your own flight wisely!
Bring a group of friends, order a flight (be sure to include the Trifecta, which is great) and try to grab the lone table in the tap room.

reviews.text: Aeronaut is as much a community center as it is a brewery.  You can find people taking on boardgames over takeout, parents chatting while rocking their infants, burlesque dancers commiserating with musicians, science discussion groups, and more.  It is very comfortable, and the beer flights are affordable and fun.  I often visit early on weekend afternoons, as the evenings get crowded and after a certain tipping point in the mid-late afternoon there is nearly always a line out the door.
Great atmosphere with friendly people. Can get a bit crowded. Definitely worth it for the fantastic locally brewed beers. Love that you can get 32 ounce cans to go and refill growlers.

I really like the beer here, and the crowd is a bit geekier than most (that's a good thing).

Problem is, they aren't allowed to fill the building to capacity, so there's almost always a 30+ minute line to get in on a Friday or Saturday night. On multiple occasions we've arrived, taken one look at the line, and gone elsewhere. Even though this location is relatively isolated for Boston.

When that issue gets resolved, Aeronaut will deserve a fifth start.
An awesome up and coming hang out spot. Be it listening to local music, playing board games, or just drinking some great beer, the place has what you are looking for.

Still one of my favorite places to get a great craft beer in the greater Boston area. They've stepped up their beer game to new levels this year.

They're really cool people too - I just came back from a snow day snowball fight they hosted there - I mean, what's better than that during a blizzard :)

Fun brewery where you can enjoy some live music and play some fun games while sipping on a nice beer.

It is also conveniently located next to Brooklyn...
