userTips.tip: Great beer, great space, very hip but not pretentiously so, lots of dogs to pet. A+

reviews.text: A very cool place! I love the ambiance and decor, plus the beers are superb as well. Anyone who bemoans the pretentious faux-industrial decor of many taprooms will appreciate the classic dive-bar groove here. Absolutely worth a visit, and you'll definitely want to come back.

Love the place.  They have great beer, I've had many different ones and they are all very good.  They obviously know how to brew beer.  The bartenders are all very personable and nice but service can be a little slow.  It's a fun place to wait!
Fantastic little tasting room. Great beer, yummy soft pretzels, super-friendly staff. Cozy tasting room that feels like a neighborhood pub.

What a solid brewery, it's local, driven, and run by mad scientists. Stop in and enjoy a great beer; perfect for any occasion in the fermentation district...keep in mind it's  an especially hot spot on Saturday.

Really fantastic! Small, cozy, warm. Amazing beers. Would recommend to anyone trying to have a good time! They even have a board game section, a Metallica pinball machine, and a Ms. Pack-Man cabinet the Joybringer, Key Lime, and Pullover are really spectacular. Lots of cool merch too! Somewhat hard to find, had to go through the door labeled CrossFit, but we'll labeled.
This is a great brewery. They have a dozen quality beers on tap and rotate frequently. You get free quality snacks with a flight purchase. There are board...

beers.beerDescription: There's not much new to say about IPAs since there are five thousand or so other commercial examples out there, but it is a style that's a personal favorite of ours - we tend to prefer hops with the big, fruity, juicy flavors that are all the rage with the young'uns these days. But since this is our mainstay year-round IPA (don't worry, hopheads, we'll have plenty more variations on the style once we're rolling) we've tried to balance that out a bit (for everyday drinkin' we tend to prefer something that doesn't necessarily smell like a fruit salad with perfume on it) with some malty goodness and a dab or two of some slightly-more-nuanced hop varieties (don't get me wrong, we're all about intense flavor. But you wouldn't want an all-syrup Squishee every day, would you?). Needless to say, this is one you'll miss in between pours.
White Ale with Key Lime juice

I used to work with a girl named Kelly who didn’t like dark beers until she drank my porter. Then every time I mentioned brewing within twenty feet of her, she’d ask, “Are you brewing your porter?” and then she’d start telling the same story I just told you, only ten thousand times longer. Eventually, I brewed the porter again in the hopes of getting her to shut up about it. It didn’t work, but the beer was a keeper.

Since we like a taste of home in our beers, we set our sights on the fabled Unicorn of American Brewing: a beer that's light (in color/body/etc.) that won't let you down in the flavor department. And lo, we done it! We took a cream ale and goosed it with some good ol' Bone Up magic, and made a tasty brew that'll disappear from your glass before you know it and then you'll have to try and convince your roommate to get you more so you don't have to get up. I’m told that the British call that “moreishness.” There, you learned something today. Go ahead and crack one open, you earned it.

In keeping with our commitment towards not dumping a bunch of weird goop in our beers, this inky black stout's made with real-ass orange peel and a whole lotta Taza cocoa nibs. It’s a surprisingly smooth sip of suds that gives you a good warm tingle in your belly.
Light bodied, citrusy dark beer brewed with witbier spices

Sometimes you just gotta have an old-school citrus-and-pine IPA, so we took some Classic American Hops and chucked them in the kettle with some Cascade from our friends down the road and mixed in just a *pinch* of Bone Up Magic. We ain't gonna strip the enamel off your teeth, but we are gonna give you a solid beer for solid times. Enjoy.

Our take on a classic Oktoberfest staple is made to showcase the toasty breadiness of grains we got from Blue Ox Malthouse, as well as some freshass fruity hoppiness from our friends at Four Star Farms. This malty masterpiece ain't gonna disappoint - Prost!

Brewed to pair with the music of the Original Gravity Concert Series, this playful lil' farmhouse ale is ready to take your tastebuds for a spin with the zip of fresh ginger, lemony hops, and the peppery spiciness of rye!
We brewed this beer to bring joy into your life (or, more accurately, because BeerAdvocate told us we needed to bring a special release to the Microbrew Invitational)!

We partnered up with the Movember Foundation for this beer, so we obviously had to go with the manliest of beer styles: brown ale. It's the chest hair of beer - not everybody likes it, but it's here to stay so you might as well just roll with it and enjoy the ride.
Dark Mild
In the honor of a sassy lil' scottie who brightened our lives until late last year, we brewed up a small sweet stout and tossed in some chipotles and black peppercorns to give it a spicy little zip!

Part Belgian Strong, part English Barleywine, part glassful of nap, the Beer of Truth will shine its light upon you and reveal what you are truly made of (odds are, it will reveal that you are made of somebody who really wants pizza right now). ​

This jaunty little wheat ale is packed full o' hops and just burstin' with floral notes and whiffs of tropical fruit. This beer is just beggin' to be quaffed as you make the most of these last summer days!

This mutt of a beer is the bastard child of a saison, a double IPA, and a tripel - born by accident and kept by happy coincidence. It has the hoppiness of an IPA, the spicy pepperiness of a tripel, and a fistful of rye. It's a sensorial thrill ride, and we don't think you'll be disappointed.

After we used Blue Ox malt for Bullhead, we were a bit smitten so we ordered a whole bunch more without really having any plan on what to make with it. Then one day, inspiration struck in the form of a terrible pun, and a plan was hatched. Similar(ish) in spirit to Bullhead, this beer is made to showcase the quality/qualities of Blue Ox malt, heavily featuring their "Vye-Enna" malt to make a light 'n' fruity BDG. Enjoy!

This is the second entry in our loosely-defined series of single-hop beers made with hops that nobody cares about. This time around we're focusing on Cluster - an old-school American hop that combines lemony citrus character (in times of shortage, it's used as a substitute for Cascade) with a bit of Wild American earthiness. It's a cool lil' hop, and we're showcasing it by using it in a a solid caramel-forward pale ale base that leans a ways toward the red end of the color spectrum.
We like to keep somethin' malty, dry, and a little roasty kickin' around, so we brewed up this humble brown ale for you!
We're more determined than ever to convince people that darker beers fare better when it's warm and sunny out, so we cooked up a toffee 'n' roast easy quaffer to show them beach beers who's boss.

As soon as she learned of Warrior's existence, Jimbo has been itchin' to use it in a single hop beer. And as luck would have it, this lil' hop fits in perfectly with our MO for single hop beers - it's largely flown under the radar (most brewers use it for bittering only) but it brings some cool flavors and aromas to the table - our "expert panel" (Jimbo and Jared drinking warm hydrometer samples) says it tastes like orange candy, but carries a strong spice-rack dried-herb aroma. Solid!

As this is our fiftieth batch, we wanted to do something with a nod towards our first-ever batch, only bigger and better. So we gathered up a figurative ton of Empire Malt, a moderately huge amount of Andrew's Honey, an impractically large amount of hops, and unleashed hell upon our brewing system! The end result is simultaneously dry and fruity, with just the slightest underlying hint of honey; we advise you to grab some while you can, since this beer ain't gonna stick around too long!
In the spooktacular spirit of Halloween, we brewed up this monster of a DIPA with a fistful of everything from the hop freezer and a buncha fun purple stuff!
Brewed for a friend of the brewery and groom-to-be, this rich and smooth chocolate stout is made to be paired with Jodi.

We took an ounce of this, a partial pound of that, a fistful of hops with no label, and threw 'em all into this aromatic delight! We couldn't recreate it if we wanted to, so come enjoy it while it's here!

BoneUpBrewingCompany.name: Bone Up Brewing Company
BoneUpBrewingCompany.breweryDescription: Our beers celebrate American styles while taking inspiration from old-school Belgian techniques. Many are new spins on classic styles (often but not always making them a bit more hop-forward), all are fermented with our house yeast blend for added complexity. We brew a few year-round beers, but our gears are always turning, so you can expect a lot of one-offs, seasonal releases, and experimental batches. We love us some brewin', and we think you're gonna enjoy the fruits of our labor!

reviews.text: A little pricy. Especially the canned beer. $21 for a 4pk is a little outrageous. Even for craft stuff. But it was good and the pizza place nearby was good too.

Really enjoy coming here.  They have a mix of unique beers with more traditional styles so almost everyone will be happy.  Also, they are dog friendly, which being an indoors only location is great for when we want a drink on a rainy day.
Relaxing atmosphere. Decent brews!

Loved checking out the brewery finally! Creative, on trend craft brews and custom winners. Most reminiscent of Allagash for me but definitely with cool branding and right in my backyard in Chelsea. The brewery has ample parking, lively energy inside and easy very easy to get to and find. Following these guys on Instagram for a long time and really love therir web presence. Would love to do a pop up with you guys sometime!

I love that Mystic is so close to us in East Boston, and was the perfect place to spend an afternoon on a lazy Sunday. They always have a good variety of beers available, no matter what your preference is. Unfortunately they didn't serve food anymore last I was here, but worth a visit regardless. If you're a fan of saisons you've definitely gotta give Mystic a try!

Mystic Brewery you are a FIVE STAR place. Drop mic. 

The last few years I have become a fan of the Brewery experience. Love to go and try the different...

beers.beerDescription: Every brewery once brewed a table beer as low alcohol everyday beer. A true beer-lovers beer; beer for beers sake. Our table beer origniated due to the generally high ABV of beers we were making being two much for a simple after work refreshment. This is one of the most loved and returned to beers we have made.

The Hum is an phenomena that occurs through the world, involving low frequency humming. It has been reported by national media in the UK and US.

That being said, The Hum, our "low-frequency" Porter, is an American take on an English Porter. Using Chinook and EKG to hop a malt build, consisting of Pilsner, Wheat, Oats, Pale Chocolate, Caramel, Dark Crystal, Carafa 3, and Maltodextrin. The end result is an extremely balanced Porter. Notes of coffee, sweet dark chocolate and leather on the nose. Medium body, allows the sweet characteristics to coat your pallet, without lingering too much, before a slight bitter finish leaves you wanting another sip.

St. Brigid's Day (Mary of the Gael) is celebrated in Ireland at the time of Imbolic, a once pagan celebration of "Summer in the Belly of Winter." This release in our series of seasonal saisons is a refreshingly hoppy take on saison for springtime. Mary of the Gael has a simple base of pilsner malt, a touch of honey malt, and is dry hopped with a copious amount of floral hops.
Farmhouse ale with cranberries
Double IPA hopped with Simcoe, Citra, equinox, Ella and Mosaic. FRUIT SALAD!
Pale ale with Amarillo and Mosaic hops
This New England version of an imperial stout is brewed with Massachusetts malted wheat and native Massachusetts yeast.
Dry-hopped sour farmhouse Ale
Voltage IPA is a crazy, hazy IPA. Developed to be juicy, delicious, vivid yet soft.
Uncarbonated "still" ale, fermented with three strains of yeast and aged in American oak.

Illegal Dance Moves puts you on a juicy rollercoaster ride through moutains of airy fruit foam, cascading down lava flows of bright hazy citrus. Yes, you read that right. This totally awesome beer is filled to the brim with Citra and Mandarina Bavaria hops making this beer taste just like a fresh tangerine.

DDH Saturation Pale Ale is a version of our hoppy pale ale which has been dry hopped a second time just before canning. Both pellets and lupulin power of Mosaic hops is thus freshly layered on top of Amarillo, Mosaic and Citra. The result is and extra-aromatic but stil crushable, juicy pale ale full of citrus and tropical fruit.
Session ale dry hopped with Citra, Mosaic and Huell Melon.
Double IPA dry-hopped with Equinox.
Saison with Ethiopian single origin coffee, made in collaboration with George Howell Coffee
White ale. A classic Belgian recipe: lightly spiced, aromatic and just slightly tart while staying light and crushable.
Triple IPA dry hopped with four different types of lupulin powder (Simcoe, Citra, Ekuanot, Mosaic)
Farmhouse Ale with Coffee.
Saison fermented in Chardonnay barrels.

userTips.tip: Best brew I've had since I moved to Boston 2 weeks ago. They're now open till 9 pm!

reviews.text: Really amazing soft pretzels! Great beer!  The tour is kinda short but you get to taste test from a good selection. The hall is almost always full to the max so it's hard to find space for any size group. The line wait can sometimes be really long. It can be really cold in the winter because it's close to the water so dress warm. Its worth going just to hang out in the beer hall.

Friendly, but not overly informative tour. We went on a Friday afternoon, which may not have been the best time to go, as most of the staff had packed in for the day and nothing was running. Tap room was very lively and the beer was great. Do make sure everyone who goes with you likes beer, though, as they sell very little else!

Hands down the best brewery tour I’ve experienced! Fantastic value. I enjoyed the private beer sample opportunity half way through the education portion of the tour. After the tour have a pretzel made from the same yeast used to make the beer and you won���t be disappointed. Delicious!! I recommended going early because the line is real after lunch.

When you first walk in, it's a very welcoming and warm atmosphere. Very loud and alive! It's a little hard to find a seat, so if you are coming during a weekend day, I recommend coming a little bit closer to opening. It took a bit for a server to make their way over to our table, but once he came he got our order right away. Our drinks came out very fast once ordered! 

It's a little tight for a large group, so maybe planning a brewery tour with a group makes more sense then trying to find seats for everyone late on a Friday night. If you decide to come without a tour, definitely fun to bring some cards or a game with a group of friends!

I love this beer hall and brewery. The beers are great, ranging from fruity unfiltered to powerful double IPAs. The tour is 5 dollars and includes a bunch of free samples. This is a great place to take your relatives or friends from out of town. Only downside is the location is a bit out of the way from downtown. I have also waited in quite a few lines on the weekends (up to an hour during peak season). But, once inside, the beer and atmosphere is always worth it. Pretzels are a must!

UFO IPA flight and beer cheese. Repeat after me: UFO IPA flight and beer cheese! YAS now you know what to order. 

Okay first of all - ALL THE SEATING...

beers.beerDescription:
We started brewing this beer as a summer seasonal in 1993.  There were some great IPAs out in the Pacific Northwest, but no local IPAs on the east coast.  We wanted to have a local IPA, so we brewed one.  People absolutely loved it, and so did we.  So we made it a year-round beer, and it’s now our bestselling beer and our flagship.
Description: Since its introduction, Harpoon IPA has remained unique in its ability to balance hop bitterness with a strong malt backbone. Dry-hopped with Cascade hops, it has a floral hop aroma and a finish that is bitter (it is an IPA after all!) without being harsh or astringent. Combined with a malty sweetness and the fruity esters of our proprietary yeast, those hops create a beer that is wonderfully hoppy but clean and refreshing enough to enjoy a few of - and we hope you do.

Light, crisp, refreshing UFO White follows in the tradition of spiced wheat beers that have been brewed in Belgium for well over 300 years. Brewed with orange peel and coriander, UFO White is the perfect choice for a summer’s barbecue, a night out with friends or any time you're thirsting for something a little different. Like all UFO beers, we leave UFO White UnFiltered.

Winter Warmer was Harpoon's first seasonal beer. It was designed to be enjoyed during the holiday season. Note the aroma of cinnamon. There is no aromatic hop added that might overpower the distinct spice scent. A smooth, medium bodied ale spiced with cinnamon and nutmeg.

It’s a simple story; we brew this beer because we like pumpkin (pumpkin pie, really) and thought an unfiltered pumpkin ale would be great, especially during the New England fall.  Turns out it is. Imagine a pumpkin vine wound its way in a field of barley, and a brewer harvested it all to make a beer. Add Northwestern hops and a blend of spices, and you've got UFO Pumpkin. The malt combination provides a smooth body and slightly sweet flavor, which balances perfectly with the earthy notes derived from the pure pumpkin. And like all of our UFO beers, UFO Pumpkin is UnFiltered.

This mango-infused Pale Ale begins with a subtle tropical aroma of passion fruit and mango. Golden-copper in color, it has a light body, slight hop bitterness, and malty sweetness, and finishes with a kiss of mango.

Harpoon Octoberfest is a malty tribute to fall, balanced by a gentle hop bitterness.  In keeping with tradition, it is a Marzen-style beer, brewed with abundant quantities of Munich, Chocolate, and Pale malts. Those malts provide a solid, full body and create the beer’s deep color.  It is a rich, flavorful beer.
A beer brewed to be enjoyed with summertime activities.  It is light, refreshing, and crisp.

We have added natural raspberry flavor to our UFO Hefeweizen to create this beer.  Consistent with the hefeweizen style, this beer is unfiltered and cloudy with a solid foamy head.  UFO Raspberry has a distinctive, hazy rose color.  The scent of fresh raspberries hits the nose immediately, along with a subtle bready aroma from the wheat and yeast.  The body is light and the unfiltered yeast provides a soft mouthfeel.  The taste of the fruit compliments the beer nicely, neither overwhelms the other.  There is a faint sweetness on the palate, which finishes cleanly in a semi-dry, tart finish.

Harpoon Leviathan Imperial IPA will challenge your senses and your palate. As the vibrant aroma rushes out of your glass you will notice the blend of piney and tropical fruit notes.  At first sip, this big beer starts with apowerful hop bitterness up front and an aggressive hop flavor and character throughout. 

Leviathan Imperial IPA is brewed with tons of pale malt and just enough caramel malt to provide a sweet malt body to balance the hop intensity. We used copious amounts of a variety of hops including Chinook, Centennial, Simcoe, and Amarillo at various points during the boil to create a complex hop flavor and clean lingering bitter finish. We then fermented the beer with Harpoonâ€™s own versatile proprietary yeast.   Finally, we dry hopped at a rate of over 1 lb a barrel to produce this beerâ€™s massive aroma.

Harpoon Take 5 was first brewed on the Brewery’s 10-barrel system in early 2014. With each pilot batch the recipe was tweaked until the desired balance between hop aroma and malt character was achieved. This final version begins with a vibrant citrus and pine hop aroma from Simcoe and Amarillo hops and follows through with a sturdy malt profile from the combination of Pale, Vienna, Carapils, and English Amber malts. Hop forward but not too bitter, low ABV but with a significant malt body – a truly sessionable beer.
The Long Thaw White IPA style blends the spiciness of a Belgian Wit and the American hop character of an IPA.

The unfiltered yeast remains in suspension, giving this style its signature cloudy color and a soft mouthfeel.  Unlike traditional Bavarian hefeweizens, however, UFO Hefeweizen uses a northern German ale yeast to produce it's signature "citrus-like" aroma.

This Hoppy Amber Ale is our tribute to the quintessential season of change. A bright hop aroma from late hop additions plays with its strong malt backbone. Amber hued, medium bodied, with hints of citrus and pine, this ale is made for the crisp days (and nights) of fall.

In 2011 Harpoon co-founders Rich Doyle and Dan Kenary brewed a Rye IPA as part of the brewery’s 100 Barrel Series. It quickly became a favorite at the brewery, so we decided to make it year-round. 

This beer is brewed with our proprietary yeast – the same yeast we’ve used since first brewing Harpoon Ale – and some interesting hop varieties. The combination of Pale, Rye, Caramel 60, Flaked Rye, and Vienna yield a complex malt body that stands up to the spiciness of the rye and the pronounced hop flavor. The rye also adds a reddish hue to the beer. The kettle additions of Centennial, Apollo, and Chinook, and the dry hop addition of Falconer’s Flight add a multidimensional hop character.

Inspired by the classic tale. Cinnamon, clove, and ginger 
combine with an unfiltered wheat beer in this deliciously 
spiced, gingerbread-inspired beer.

Our head brewer at our Windsor brewery homebrewed a batch of chocolate stout for himself after trying the style at a beer dinner and loving it.  After several Harpooners tried Scott’s batch, we knew that we needed to add this beer to our lineup. It was originally introduced as a limited edition extra in our winter mix pack back in 2008, but it was soon apparent that our drinkers wanted more of this beer (a beer made with chocolate…not too hard to understand!), so we brought it back in 6-packs in 2010.

A chocolate stout is a beer with a noticeable dark chocolate flavor. This flavor is created from the use of darker, more aromatic malt that has been roasted or kilned until it acquires a chocolate color. Harpoon Chocolate Stout is brewed with an abundance of chocolate malt and a touch of chocolate.
A Double IPA that's slightly sweet with a lingering bitterness.
Golden and refreshing, flavorful but smooth, with a crisp, dry finish. A balancing act of the finest ingredients for a refreshing new breed of craft beer.

Harpoon Cider is crafted from only one ingredient: freshly pressed apples. We ferment it with our house yeast, yielding a clean but refreshing all natural cider. 
Harpoon Cider is also naturally gluten-free. Its gluten content has been independently measured at less than 20 parts per million, meeting the FDA's proposed threshold for gluten-free.
This draft-only Irish stout was made with six different types of malt, including roasted and chocolate, with a small dose of Willamette hops.

Hop forward without being bitter, this single hop Pale Ale showcases the piney, citrusy character of Centennial hops. Bright and golden, light and drinkable, the subtle malt flavor lets the hops shine.
Winter Blonde Cold Brew Ale, with vanilla and coffee notes.

Having brewed in South Boston since 1987, it was probably only a matter of time before we decided to commemorate St. Patrick’s Day (Evacuation Day - coincidentally a holiday - in Boston).  It’s a beer that we thought would pair well with the late winter as well: malty enough to stand up to the cold but balanced enough to hint at Spring. 

Harpoon Celtic Ale features a deep ruby color, medium body, and a balanced malt bill created by Irish Ale malt and a touch of roasted barley. Rich in tradition and sessionable in character, Harpoon Celtic is the ideal Spring seasonal.

Natural huckleberry flavor is added to this hefeweizen to make it the perfect blend of sweet and refreshing for any and all summer fun. Pairs nicely while frolicking through the countryside. And what the heck does a huckleberry taste like? A blueberry. But better.

HarpoonBrewery.name: Harpoon Brewery
HarpoonBrewery.breweryDescription: Love Beer. Love Life. Employee-Owned, brewed in Boston, MA and Windsor, VT.

userTips.tip: That's right, 20 beers on tap, including rare brews from their "10-barrel pilot system" that you can't get anywhere else.
So many bearded men work here!
Free tastings in theSouth Boston Waterfront brewery weekdays are at 4 p.m.; there is an additional tasting at 2 p.m. on Wednesdays, Thursdays, and Fridays.
The cider is made from apples from Harvard, Massachusetts (about 40 minutes away from the brewery). Makes a delicious brew.

Hot as shweaty bawls in here....no air conditioning!?? Its a 90 degree day in Boston...Get it ogether, Harpoon!!  The only redeeming quality tonight is the parmesan pretzel with marinara...phenomenal.
They only serve beer and pretzels, but that's more than enough to make this a must-visit location next time I'm in Boston. Staff is friendly and barkeeps are more than happy to share Harpoon history.
"Cheese IPA" are the only two words you need to utter when ordering pretzel dips.
Delicious beer and pretzels. Make sure to ask about the rotating pilot batches of beer!! Mmm lemon elderberry ale.
This little brewery is now served all over the country and has 2 breweries (one here and on in Windsor, VT). Take the tour and enjoy some free samples!
The hour long tasting is the BEST!
Coffee porter is delicious. Dark and actually refreshing.
Get the pretzels! And the Triunfo. #beer
FREE tastings every weekday from 2-4pm and weekend tours most of the day for just $5. Boston Beer - the best around.
Go to a beer tasting and reward yourself by tasting the fine beer!

reviews.text: It may not be a "real authentic brewery tour" but it is a real authentic good time. I love the fact they go into depth explaining the process and they fact they give you a keepsake to take with you. A nice detour to take if your in the area.

They lose a star as this isn't really a big production facility that's good for tours, but it was a fun stop for any Sam Adams lover. The taproom was small but nice and the bartenders there were knowledge and friendly. Worth stopping in, just don't get your hopes too high for an amazing tour.

Great tour, free beer. Tap room is great for trying the new experimental batches. Tour guide was entertaining, engaging with the whole group, and very knowledgeable. Really solid hour, two if you include wandering around the gift shop and tap room.

Not so much a brewery tour but more like an excuse to drink samples for free. The actual 'brewery tour' was 5 minutes behind a barrier looking at some stainless equipment from 40ft away. This tour is not actually at one of their production breweries but at a small test facility. Also none of the beer they serve you is brewed there. I've been to actual brewery tours before and this isn't that.

I wouldn’t complain about a free brewery tour with ample tastings, but I would rate this tour five stars even if it cost money. It’s one of the best brewery tours around, largely because of the high quality of the guides. Don’t forget to leave time for a stop at Doyle’s after to pick up your free glass.
This was our second time at the brewery our last visit was over 3 years ago. Since, it was a cold and rainy day plus, our hotel was across the street from...

beers.beerDescription: Samuel Adams Boston Lager® is the best example of the fundamental characteristics of a great beer, offering a full, rich flavor that is both balanced and complex. It is brewed using a decoration mash, a time consuming, traditional four vessel brewing process discarded by many contemporary brewers. This process brings forth a rich sweetness from the malt that makes it well worth the effort. Samuel Adams Boston Lager® also uses only the finest of ingredients including two row barley, as well as German Noble aroma hops. The exclusive use of two row barley not only imparts a full, smooth body but also gives the beer a wide spectrum of malt flavor ranging from slightly sweet to caramel to slightly roasted. The Noble hops varieties, Hallertau Mittelfruh and Tettnang Tettnanger, add a wide range of floral, piney and citrus notes, which are present from the aroma, through the flavor, to the lingering smooth finish. We take great pride in the Noble hops used in our beers. They are hand selected by Jim Koch and our other brewers from the world's oldest hops growing area. Among the world's most expensive, they cost twenty times as much as other hops.

In 1810, the Oktoberfest tradition was born when Munich celebrated the Crown Prince’s wedding with a special beer and 16 day party. Our version of this classic style blends rich malts for a hearty, smooth flavor with notes of caramel creating a brew that’s perfect for the season, or whatever you’re celebrating.

Samuel Adams® Summer Ale is an American wheat ale. This hazy golden unfiltered brew combines crisp wheat with the bright citrus of lemon peel and the subtle spice of Grains of Paradise.  This rare African pepper, closely related to cardamom, was first used as a brewing spice in the 13th Century and adds just the right peppery kick. All of these flavors come together to create a thirst quenching and utterly refreshing brew perfect for those warm summer days.

Bold and rich, with a touch of holiday spice
The first thing one notices in a Samuel Adams® Winter Lager is its color: the deep brown of winter. Then comes the magical aroma which promises something special on the tongue. The warm aroma of cinnamon and ginger which blends with the toasty sweetness of the malted barley and hint of citrus.
A White Ale brewed with a blend of fresh ground spring spices including orange, plum, and fresh ground coriander.

Perfect for any summer day, Samuel Adams® Porch Rocker was inspired by traditional Bavarian Radlers that mix beer with German-style lemonade.  For our bright and citrusy Radler, we blended a Helles beer with lemon for a fresh-squeezed lemon taste, effervescent sweetness, and slightly tart, refreshing finish.  A light malt character and hint of hops balance out this summer brew.

As crisp as the first snowfall of the year, this unfiltered white ale is blended with holiday spices including cinnamon, nutmeg, and orange peel.  The familiar citrus and wheat characters of the ale are complemented by the warmth of the spices for a festive brew that’s perfect for the season.

Ale brewed with Cherries, crisp and fruity with a hint of honey.  Samuel Adams Cherry Wheat® follows the centuries old American tradition of brewing beer with native ingredients, in this case Michigan cherries as well as a touch of honey. The sweet fruitiness of the cherries is balanced against the crisp, cereal note from the malted wheat and the subtle citrus flavor from the Noble hops. The end result is a sweet, refreshing beer that is light on the palate but long on complexity.

Spicy and Bold, a big Christmas cookie of a beer.
Samuel Adams® Old Fezziwig® Ale is the Christmas cookie of beer. Bursting with spices of the season and a remarkably full body, it helps those long winter nights pass much quicker. The full body hits the palate first with a depth of malt character ranging from sweeter toffee and caramel notes to the more dark, roasty chocolate notes. Then come the spices in full force. Cinnamon, ginger and orange peel dance on the tongue bringing with them the celebratory spirit that goes hand in hand with the season.

Brewed with real grapefruit for an added punch of citrusy goodness that amplifies the tropical fruit and citrus notes from the hops.  A hint of juiciness rounds out the bitterness and brings a refreshing finish to this bold, bright, thirst-quenching IPA.
This double IPA is big, brewed with over 5 lbs per barrel of American and Australian hops, and packed with fruity, citrus, pine, and resin notes for a bold hop finish. Cheers!

Four types of West Coast hops (Chinook, Citra, Centennial and Zeus) add bold notes of pine and juicy grapefruit to this deep golden wheat ale, for a crisp flavor that’s a refreshing escape from winter’s lingering chill.

This dark beer has a big, malty character with the added sweetness of chocolate. Chocolate Bock is slowly aged on a bed of rare dark cocoa nibs, the primary ingredient in chocolate. Known for their quality, these cocoa nibs harvested in Ecuador, impart complex aromas and flavors from chocolaty to fruity, nutty, earthy, and citrusy.

A unique brew that combinines the intense hop character of an IPA with the crisp spicy wheat character of a Belgian-style white ale. The white ale and IPA combination make this crisp, smooth, yet hop-friendly beer the perfect pairing with a variety of meats and cheeses. Brewed with apricots and spices.
The soft citrus of orange blossom gives this Helles lager a bright note and complements its sweet honey malt, leading to a smooth round finish.

Samuel Adams Noble Pils is one of the only brews made with all five Noble hops from the world's growing regions. its bright flavor and lively, citrus hop character reminds us that the warm days of spring are just a few weeks away.

A crisp, refreshing version of a traditional Belgian beer. Fruity, slightly spicy flavors from the Belgian yeast are balanced by toffee and caramel notes from our blend of malts. The hops provide a citrus character that rounds out this enjoyable brew.

Malty and slightly sweet, balanced by earthy notes from the hops.  The gentle rain and fertile soil of Ireland helped inspire this style of ale, known for being remarkably balanced. Pale and Caramel malts give the beer its rich, deep red color and distinctive caramel flavor. The sweetness of the malt is pleasantly balanced by a pronounced hop bitterness and an earthy note from the East Kent Goldings hops. Samuel Adams® Irish Red finishes smooth and leaves you wanting to take another sip.
Swirling with ripe aromas of mango and tropical fruits, this IPA is jam-packed with juicy, citrusy hops and mango juice.  It’s as if we took fresh hops and mangos and put them in a juicer.
Our take on the classic hybrid style from Cologne Germany, Escape Route combines the subtle fruit notes of an ale with the smooth crispness of a lager for a bright, refreshing brew.

beers.beerName: Samuel Adams Merry Maker Gingerbread Stout
beers.beerDescription: Gingerbread stout brewed with cinnamon, cloves, nutmeg, and ginger as well as well as East Kent Goldings & Fuggles hops
The distinct hop character of an IPA in a smooth lager.  The hops in this brew lend a bright grapefruit, citrus, floral aroma and flavor with a refreshing, crisp lager finish.

Amber, smooth, and resinous, this ale was inspired by our exploration of Australian hops.  We discovered that their rugged, spicy and piney character brightened a back-bone of roasted caramel malts, creating a beer with surprising depth and smoothness.

WHITE CAPPED AND LIVELY – the frothy white head of this distinctive nitro brew softly cascades into bright gold.   The first sip reveals a smooth velvety taste with a light wheat character and hints of orange while an undercurrent of peppery spice adds a bright finish.

DARKLY ENTICING – smooth, velvety cream cascades into a jet black brew revealing a rich, robust character.  The dark roasted malts create notes of bittersweet chocolate with hints of dark fruit while the Sumatran & Indian Monsoon Malabar coffees develop a deep roasty dimension.

SamuelAdamsBrewery.name: Boston Beer Company
SamuelAdamsBrewery.breweryDescription:
Jim Koch founded the Boston Beer Company back in 1984 after brewing the first batch of Samuel Adams Boston Lager in his kitchen. It was his mission to reshape the way American beer drinkers thought of American beer. 

Just six weeks after introducing Samuel Adams Boston Lager to the public, it brought home the "Best Beer in America" honors at the Great American Beer Festival in Denver. An honor it went on to win 3 more times before that particular award was discontinued.

Today, Samuel Adams makes more than 21 styles of award winning beer and is recognized around the globe as a hot house of new beer ideas.

If you share our passion, join us here as a fan! 

Cheers!

The Boston Beer Company, Boston MA

userTips.tip: "I keep asking for my own flavor of Sam Adams, and they keep telling me that 'Bubblegum Cough Syrup' would never sell." - Conan O'Brien
Free tours and tastings at the brewery between 10 a.m. and 3 p.m. Mon. - Thurs., plus Saturdays (the tours leave every 45 minutes or so). On Fridays, tours continue through 5:30 p.m.
Take a fun and informative tour through the Samuel Adams Brewery. Plus free beer is part of the tour.
FREE brewery tour, FREE beer tastings, and a FREE tasting glass - how can you go wrong?
Go to Sam Adams Brewery, take the tour, get some free beer.
When you go they'll generally give you three different beers. The first two are the Boston Lager and the current Seasonal beer. The third changes and is usually something unique and/or special.
Don't hog the pitchers!
Mail out a postcard for free from the gift shop.  Stay near the back of the tour on the third stop (the large steel barrel room) to get a prime seat in the tasting room.
If visiting from out of town, take the T to get there.  The mileage isn't far, but by foot you pass through some "interesting" neighborhoods.
Go on a brewery tour to learn all about the beer making process. Oh, and to sample!
The tour is free and you get to sample three beers and keep the tasting glass. The tour guide was really funny and entertaining. Lots of fun! Go to Doyle's for food and keep your Sam Adams glass.

reviews.text: Very good food and beer. The Personnel is very polite and the environment cozy and joyful. It is and will remain my favorite place for hanging out with good friends.

My favorite place to go in Boston. It's big enough to bring a lot of folks together and small enough to stop by after class to get some beer and watch some baseball. Staff has always been friendly and helpful. Plus, they have a gender-neutral restroom.
Willing to deal with large crowds. Whether it's eating or drinking, John Harvard's is always solid! Excellent Española.
Friendly staff, and great food. Portions are big, but not overly so. You probably won't have any leftovers to take home, especially since the food is so yummy it's hard to stop eating.

This place has a good vibe. Had drinks at the bar before our party arrived, very slow service. Once we were seates, things got better. Our server was at super star, but it did take awhile to get our food. Thankfully the food was great!

I love John Harvard's. Been going to John Harvard's since 1999 and their seasonal beers are amazing. 

They have an amazing atmosphere that makes you feel...

beers.beerDescription: Juicy, Hazy orange, soft carbonation, plush fruity aromas. Immense mango, marmalade, pine, honeysuckle, and lemon flavors. Smack dab in between Lambo and Tesseract on the sweet-to-dry spectrum. Just a hint of bitterness.
Juicy, aromatic DIPA with tropical fruit for days.
We in this bitch.  Finna get crunk.  Gummi bear juice on fleek.  Citra, Simcoe, El Dorado you already know what it is.

2015 GABF gold medal and 2014 GABF silver medal in the imperial stout category.  Double Negative pours jet black with burnt orange highlights.  A long lasting tan head leaves abundant lacing. Aromas bursting from the glass include espresso, bitter chocolate, caramel, black currant and blueberry.  Creamy and viscous on the palate, the flavor initially follows the nose.  A pop of smooth bitterness comes after, and then a lingering, roasty finish.
American wild/sour ale brewed with apricots, dry hopped with El Dorado, Columbus, and Cascade, and conditioned on oak.  Crush crush crush.

Super Spruce owes its immense pine aromatics to a double dose of resin. The new growth of spruce trees layered with Chinook hops create a complex profile of fresh pine that includes floral, citrus, cola, and bubble gum undertones. This unboiled beer is luminous and hazy with a grapefruit-like acidity that perfectly showcases the bright coniferous flavors. Sea salt rounds the mouthfeel, while white oak provides tannic structure.
Tart wild ale dry hopped with Mosaic, El Dorado, and Jarrylo.  Conditioned on American white oak.  Notes of guava, pineapple and other juicy, ripe tropical fruits.

Beautifully hazed-up new school IPA.  Juicy and soft with an aroma that catches your attention from across the room.  Velvety mouthfeel, soft bitterness.  Citra, Mosaic, Equinox, and El Dorado varietals kicking out a range of tropical flavors.  Perfectly balanced and dialed in.  Draft only.  Born on 1/11/16.

Hazy and richly aromatic. Aggressively dry hopped with new German aroma hops Mandarina Bavaria and Huell Melon; orange zest to boot. Lightly toasted white oak provides tannins and mouthfeel. Assertively tart, with light sea salt appearing on the finish. Citrus and hop flavors galore. Absolutely mouthwatering.

Telekinesis is a hoppy, tart, and smashable American wild ale fermented with a mixed culture of yeast and spontaneous microbes. Mosaic, Citra, and Falconer’s Flight hops contribute peachy, tropical hop character. Lightly toasted white oak spirals lend subtle tannin structure, while our no-boil process leaves a puckering hint of raw sourdough.
Refreshing, crushable dry hopped sour ale featuring hops from Germany and New Zealand (Huell Melon, Hallertau Blanc, Southern Cross) and conditioned on white oak.
"Dessert berliner" brewed with tart cherries, raspberries, vanilla, and milk sugar.
Single IPA brewed with oats, featuring Rakau hops against background elements of Citra, Mosaic, and Columbus.
Batch 2 (December 2016) Color Field is entirely reformulated from batch 1 (Jan 2015).  Raw, dry hopped sour ale brewed with hibiscus, rose hips, chamomile, and huell melon hops.
Hallertau Blanc and Galaxy.
Brewed with blackberries and blueberries, conditioned on oak, and dry hopped with hüll Melon.
Blackcurrants, raspberries, aged hops, new oak.  Juicy, tart, tannic, delicious.
Double dry hopped banger featuring galaxy, wai-iti, mosaic, and citra hops.

Conditioned in stainless tanks with oak spirals and tart Montmorency cherries, this is a shamelessly unfaithful tribute to the red-brown beers of Flanders we love so much.  Lightly toasted bread on the nose, sweet and tart on the palate, with a touch of cherry on the long, complex finish.
DIPA brewed with rotating NZ hops.  Batch 2, December 2015 release features Wai-iti and Southern Cross: wine-like notes of grape, pear, red plum, cantaloupe.

reviews.text: Amazing selection of beers on tap. A nice assortment of bottled beers from all over the world. The ambiance is nice, cozy and conducive to hanging out with friends. The staff is friendly and knowledgeable about all of the beers they sell. Check it out!

Love the huuuuuge communal table in the back. However, the arm chairs were way more comfortable. Cool art in bathroom.

The friendly staff takes the comfortable chairs and communal seating and makes it feel like your living room. They'll let you sample beers before buying and are great for a chat at the bar. After talking to them, head to the main table, and you'll likely make friends with some strangers over Jenga or just good beer. 

The kitchen does turn off around 10, but they're always fine with outside food. Bobwhite's is right next door and has a chicken sandwich you're going to want to try.
Great rotating beer selection on draft and lots of variety for to go beers. Also have good charcuterie and cheese boards.

The aggressively hopped “Alpha Male” stands center of attention with its robust and alluring hop aromas of earthy and fruity flavors and is perfectly balanced by a subtle malt character. Extra hoppy and overtly over the top, paired with a seductively crisp undertone.

beers.beerDescription: With Huell Melon and Mosaic

Paying homage to our roots on both coasts, we’ve combined the big juicy mouthfeel of a New England Style IPA with a clean fermenting West Coast Yeast, to bring you the best of both worlds.  We keep the IBUs low, the beer unfiltered, and the dry hop huge; meaning you get that juicy punch, but you’re not going to be chewing on it!  Four malts add a depth of flavor, old school Cascade, Centennial and Amarillo hops provide the beautifully floral and citrus accompaniment, and viola A Bicoastal IPA!  Well balanced, easy drinking, and complex enough for even the most attentive beer drinker to discover a new flavor with every sip.  Enjoy!

The second chapter to a crowd favorite, Tami 1. Juicy, refreshing, and clean. Mango + citrus is the name of the game this time around. 2-row, Maris Otter + flaked oats. Amarillo and Citra bittering. Amarillo and Mosaic late additions.

I went by the other night for the first time since the opened the larger tap room.  While the beers were still great the vibe of the new taproom was much different from the old one and I was not a huge fan.

The new taproom is very bright and sterile, the dark grungy look of the original tap room was lost. At 9 PM on a Friday night it was so bright it was almost like day time. 

The old taproom is still visible through a window and I am assuming the utilize it from time to time for either can releases or larger events but I am not sure.

However, if you are a fan of IPAs make sure to check this place out as you won't be disappointed.

Definitely a cool hipster type place. If you like IPAs then it's even better for you to visit. Day I went it was insanely busy and you had to wait outside on a line to get in. Other than that definitely worth a stop if your a fan of beer and even more so if your an IPA fan.
Best of the best...must visit if you know something about craft beer. although if you do not know, then this is the place where you will understand what you should drink!

OtherHalfBrewingCompany.breweryDescription: Other Half Brewing Company was founded in 2014 by Samuel Richardson and Matt Monahan. We brew craft beers for draft consumption, bottles, and cans in limited release. We believe local breweries play an important role in their communities which is why, despite the challenges of running a brewery in NYC, we couldn’t choose anywhere but Brooklyn as our home. The brewery is located on the edge of Carroll Gardens, only two blocks from the subway. Our tap room is open to the public and we also offer tours of our brewery (by appointment).

Try the beard flight.
Some of the best beers you'll find in the city, this is a must visit for any serious beer people!
Get the All Green Everything. And here's the entrance if you're like me and walked around the block twice to find it.

reviews.text: Cool place for an up and coming brewery with a unique approach to beer. Check out the SSS or the Keen, though all of the beers are an interesting mix of herbs/spices and fruits. The whiskey barrel aged coffee beans are also worth picking for brewing at home.

I had the Prima #3 dark and Floridian. Very different beers, both very good. The place is not what I expected as it's on the 6th floor and they serve liquor as well. Almost no brewery feel to it all as it was jammed with the modern hipster. If that's your thing, this is your place
The keen sour is especially nice.

beers.beerDescription: This malty ale is brewed with citrusy hops and a portion of hibiscus for color. It exhibits a red hue and tangy finish.
Pleasantly askew. Light ale spiked with green tea leaves and nutmeg for a playfully palatable pint. The feather-light bubbles and creaminess are inclined to delight.

Sensational beer for the sensationalist. Simply put, this super dark ale has splendid spiciness, slight sweetness and a singe of smokiness, with zero superfluous extras. Its sizable spirit makes it superb for sipping.
A family favorite, this ale is brewed with tropical hops and a smattering of citrus zest. It exhibits flavors of lemon, mango, grapefruit, pear, and pine.
A boisterous ale! Exhibiting citrus flavor and aromas with added tanginess from interjections of hibiscus. It’s red hue and hoppy bite make for an exciting pint.
Pre-prohibition. Inspired by an old, new world beer. This dark ale is brewed with corn and molasses. It's soft, roasty and historical.
An experimental creation. Brewed with lemon zest, honey, mint, and all 100% New York State ingredients. The blend of flavors make for a refreshing delight!
Dark ale brewed with traditonal Coquito ingredients. Coconut, vanilla, cinnamon, and rum.

An experimental creation. Brewed with fresh, green cardamom pods and cinnamon, this dark ale exhibits rich spice flavors to compliment its roasted malts. The herbal and spicy aromas add an enchanting twist to the ale.
Tropical Twist! A mix of the tastiest tropical fruit and an ancient beer herb. This ale is brewed with cantaloupe, coconut and basil.
A zinger! Our collaboration with Rockaway Brewing Co. This ale is brewed with acerola, a cherry-like fruit. It's tart and refreshing!
Punch of citrus. A sour ale produced with a healthy portion of kumquats, and mango. Its dry finish and fruit-forward flavors produce a tangy bite.

Reconstructed inspiration. A masterful blend of unique ingredients gives this amber ale notes of citrus, pepper, ginger, and soft hints of licorice. Balanced and palatable, these flavors create delightful drinkability.
Foreign familiarity. This sour ale is brewed to tradition with the addtion of ingredients from across the world. It’s sour, savory, and sweet all at once.
What's the fuss? This hoppy ale packs the punch and excitement of American hops and is brewed with grapefruit zest. It finishes crisp and dry.

Homage to the Homeland. Our collaboration brew with Island to Island Brewery and a blending of carribean flavors from the islands. Brewed with hibiscus and lychee this ale packs a pinch and a lot of flavor.
A heavenly ale brewed with lavender. The light, flowery aroma dances between with the biscuit and nutty notes in this ale.
Family Meeting. The collective palates of the Wartega Family has created this ale brewed with figs, maple and ginger. It's balanced, fruity with a hint of spice.

Modesty in moderation. What this ale lacks in size, it makes up with big swinging hops.  The powerful fruit and pine aroma will envelop you. It just goes to show that it's not the size of the beer that counts it's how it feels in your mouth!
A stroll through New York State. This ale is brewed with New York ingredients and a New York state of mind. It has a rich grain flavor and hints of earthy and woodsy notes!

Wartega.breweryDescription: Wartega is NYC's only brewery specializing in beers carefully crafted with herbs, spices and fruits; inspired by ancient ale ingredients with uniquely bold flavor.

I LOVE Six Point beverages!  I think if you want one of the best beers with a lot of taste, you try one of these!  The brewery takes the time to exact a recipe that stands out above many other micro breweries.  Try one!
I drank a candidate beer and it’s fabulous

beers.beerDescription: "Resin" is named after the sticky ooze that secretes from the lupulin glands of the hop cone.
This is the new version of Bengali (originally named Bengali Tiger)
The original Sehr Crisp from Sixpoint. Brewed with noble hops for indelible sehr crisp flavor.

...Once our eyes were opened to the potential of the hop cone, we couldn’t be stopped. With a laser focus, we magnified the hop factor, and pushed the boundaries of flavor, aroma, and perception itself to create HI-RES. It’s Mad Science.

It may be the calm before the storm, but no one can deny the beer climate is changing. Season(al)s are creeping, traditional styles are melting down, and storm clouds are rolling in. Sounds like it’s time for an updated formulation — a different sort of winter warmer for a changing globe. A cloudy, unfiltered, hop-intensified Global Warmer should do the trick. Or, we could kid ourselves and deny the whole thing…
If you love Resin, try tasting it straight from the tanks. That’s Puff – a hazy, unfiltered pour straight from the tanks, with an extra dose of dry hops... a new blend devised just for Puff.
The unmistakeable flavor of a Bavarian Wheat, but with a clear golden brilliance and a Sixpoint twist. An entirely unique canned offering for the sun-worshipping ale lovers.
You started with cream in your coffee, now have coffee in your cream ale. Pour up a bright blonde coffee ale and end your day the way you started it. With a delicious craft brew.
The Mad Scientists kept tweakin' that jammer until it rocked just right:  grains, water, & salt make up this flavorful and simple brew.
Made with Rye malt to provide a signature and distinct earthy character. Seasoned and dry-hopped with herbal and citrus hops. Truly Righteous.
This undefinable black brew is part black IPA, part American Stout, but 100% Diesel powered. Robust chocolate and roasted flavors, with thick pine hop flavor and aroma.

…my ancestors danced around a campfire and drank strange brews. Many Beasts were present. The drums were pounding; the rhythm was jamming. Let’s keep the fire going, and the ritual. Love your Beast… its Mad Science.
Sixpoint Cycliquid Designed by the Mad Scientists.  Made with a proprietary blend of five fruit juices and beer.

...It was said Tesla would visualize fully functioning inventions in his mind before even setting pen to paper. To start with a realized formulation in the mind's eye—see it, smell it, and taste it, then harness the right materials to create it?  Now that's Mad Science.

Think the juicyness of big doses of American Hops, with that clean snappiness of a cold fermented, meticulously lagered beer.
Brownstone is our bedrock; the first fortress of Sixpoint. This mahogany-hued brew has elements of roasted barley and a hop-forward profile.
American Pale Ale - Saison hybrid.

It's time for a sesher. Hi-Res magnified the Resin. Now, let's change the resolution. When you zoom out from the hop cone, things can get grainy. Focus on the juice - that'll bring the pixels back into perspective.
Robust and rich Porter made with coffee beans from Gorilla Coffee in Park Slope, Brooklyn
A kettle-soured Berliner Weiss fermented with loads of raspberries. Puckering but still refreshing. Raspberries plus lactic acid remind us of raspberry lemon sorbet.
A smooth, creamy oatmeal stout with a light sweetness and dry finish. Full roasted flavor without a touch of harshness, often poured on nitro-tap.

This is a classic Kölsch with an exclusive twist — growers at Hopfengut in Germany recently released the Huell Melon hop strain, with the clean bittering qualities of noble hop strains, but an elusive “honey-dew melon” aroma. So for Köld Schauer think easy-drinking, low bitterness, with a unique perfume. Those pilgrimages we’ve been taking to German hop fields are paying dividends…
If you have long enjoyed the single wonders of Sweet Action, prepare to double it.
2018 formulation with unique dry-hop bill, and unfiltered before packaging.
Fruity Galaxy hops meet the souring capabilities of Lactobacillus. Tangy and refreshing, with an inviting peachy-lemon aroma-flavor combo.

beers.beerDescription: THE REDEFINITION OF THE SESSION IPA. Orange zest, pine resin and tropical lupulin beauty that easily rivals much bigger IPAs, with a substantially full, soft malt body that compliments but doesn’t interfere with the hop attack. When you want the push, weight, and attack of a much heavier (I)IPA but need to be productive tomorrow –  One of our proudest accomplishments.

Bridge and Tunnel Brewery is a Queens based nano-scale micro-brewery, launched by brewer/proprietor: Rich Castagna. At the present time, the brewery is operating as a one-man brewing operation, with the help from Rich's wife Lisa with the various additional tasks necessary to keep a brewery afloat. 

Rich has been brewing for over 10 years, and enjoys brewing and drinking darker beers, and beers with a flavorful kick. So the current line leans toward beers that are colorful in the glass (as well as on the palate). 

Rich was born and raised in Western Queens, and spent most of his life in the New York area short of about 8 years living and traveling around the U.S. and overseas. Over the past 15 years, he's lived in the Ridgewood/Bushwick area, Long Island City, Astoria, and Maspeth. He has 3 kids, 3 cats, a dog, a fish, a large amount of brewing equipment, and a very patient wife.

In 1642, the first Dutch Colonists came to Queens (present day Maspeth). But within that first year, they got their asses kicked, then booted out (back to Manhattan Island) by the Mespeatches Native American tribe (origins of the name 'Maspeth'). This beer is a recipe using ingredients that those first Dutch colonists would have had access to in 1642. Barley and Cluster hops were available at the time but often in short supply, so to supplement a recipe, colonial brewers used corn, rye, wheat, oats, buckwheat, and honey in their grain bills. To supplement bittering hops if in short supply, spruce tips would be used. All above ingredies are included in this recipe. The rsult is a balanced, sessiony ale - slightly cloudy (from the wheat), slightly earthy and bitter (from the spruce addition) - with a story to ponder... Sort of the 'b' side version of the story of Thanksgiving. 
Call it a colonial pale, old fashioned ale, a gruit, or whatever category you think fits.

reviews.text:
We can't say enough about Threes!  We frequently swing by on the weekend to sample from their innovative beer list, and this past fall we hosted our wedding there, and we're so glad that we did!

The backyard area fits a large crowd, and with such a pretty backdrop there isn't much needed in the way of additional decoration.  The Meat Hook provided more than enough food to keep our friends and family happy, including vegetarian and vegan options.  

The best part in hosting an event at Threes, though, is the incredible staff.  Gretchen helped us plan every detail of the event, and was quick to respond to all of our questions.  On the day of the event, the entire Threes staff was incredibly accommodating, making sure things went off without a hitch.  Our wedding was one of the happiest days of our lives and, thanks to Threes, stress-free (with plenty of beer)!

We would absolutely host an event there again soon!

I came here for the first time with a few friends on a busy Saturday night. It was pretty crowded outside (where they have heated tents) so our best bet for space was to sit inside across from the main bar. The music was too loud to hear anyone else but the person next to you, and the lighting was too dim to read the extensive menu (I swear, my generation will be blind and deaf by the time we're 50). 

It would have been a better experience had we been able to sit outside, so maybe next time I'll try to come earlier or visit on a weekday. It was also a bit of a struggle trying to order drinks, because it was hard to get out of the booth we were in and squeeze our way up to the bar. It would have been nice to offer table service or a better ordering system. 

But overall, the vibe and the beers were great, and we had a fun time. Just know what to expect when coming here.

The bar tender was happy to give us a tour of what amounted to an over-sized homebrew system (that was rapidly growing). I straight up love this place. The first time I came by a few years ago, they were to-go only, but now you can actually post up and drink your beer. Intimate brewery space, the clientele are polite and well-behaved, and Rob, Tanya, and Anthony are super affable and generous. My only worry is that this place will continue to blow up (see Other Half Brewing) and you won't be able to even stand in there anymore. 
The beers are fantastic, rustic European ales. I like the balance between trusted beers like golden ales and more exotic things like saisons made with grape must. They take interesting risks but also stick to tried an true classics.

beers.beerDescription: A dank and hazy East Coast style IPA hopped with Pacific Northwest and New Zealand hops, this juicy IPA is bound to leave you wanting more. Leading with strong tangerine flavors and notes of melon, lychee, and gooseberry, this refreshing IPA is almost too easy to drink.

Pouring a beautiful gold, this easy-drinking beer is our take on a classic style. Hopped with Sorachi Ace, Cascade, and Centennial hops. 
 Herbal and lemon notes on the aroma, followed by a mellow lemongrass and bready flavor with a crisp, dry finish.

beers.beerDescription: Flagship American Wit is a refreshing, light bodied wheat beer. Prized hops from America’s northwest region give this ale a citrusy flavor blended with the subtle undertones of our hand ground spices. A balancing malt profile contributes a recognizable golden color in addition to a slight haze from the yeast.

A showcase of some of Flagship’s favorite hop varieties and executed by using them in abundance. Each hop in IPA lends a unique flavor that when blended produces bursting fruit flavors from citrusy grapefruit to tropical mango in harmony with an ever so slight roast character from the golden malted barley. Designed for full hop flavor experience without overpowering bitterness.

Flagship Brewery’s “Metropolitan Lager” is a golden lager that features toasted Vienna and Rye malts. The Rye adds a smooth mouthfeel while floral noble hops are used in abundance for flavor and aroma. This lager is smooth, clean, crisp and exceptionally balanced.

The hop profile of Flagship APA includes an upfront bitterness complemented with citrus and pine-like aromas followed by a small burst of tropical fruit. Malted barley provides a deep auburn color and a sweet, biscuit-like backbone helping the flavor balance nicely with the bitterness from the hops. The mouthfeel is medium bodied with a hoppy and crisp finish.

A foundation consisting of American wheat and Golden Promise malts give this beer light sweetness and a slight haze. The all-star of this ale is a hop called “Summer.” This spawn of the noble hop, Saaz, is subtle and used in abundance contributing slight aromas of hop spice, earthiness, and tropical melon. American ale yeast helps to provide a crispness that is dry but balanced. Deep yellow color and a light body make this summer beer approachable and sessionable.

A malty brew that uses Vienna and Munich varieties of malted barley that are complemented with German malted rye and German chocolate rye. Bavarian noble hops balance the beer with a mild bitterness and soft floral aroma. The result is a full-bodied dark copper colored ale with a smooth texture and spicy-like characteristic from the rye malt.

Flagship Dark Mild is black in color due to a complex malt profile that’s packed with flavor by using a wide variety of roasted, toasted, and caramel malts. The mildness comes from a soft hop character and lower alcohol content making this light bodied ale a sessionable salute to our fondness for dark beer.

As we approach the inevitable winter, Flagship introduces “Wee Heavy.”  Brewed in the style of strong Scottish ales, a longer boil adds “caramelization” to the brewing process and helps produce a full body and higher alcohol content in addition to malty sweetness. We Americanize this dark brown colored beer by using a copious amount of pacific northwest hops.

The pairing of Stout with oysters has been enjoyed for centuries and Flagship Oyster Stout combines the two into one delicious apéritif. Roasted barley united with chocolate rye, midnight wheat, and flaked oats gives this brew dark color and roasty flavor while providing a smooth mouthfeel and rich body. The flavor blends nicely with a mineral brininess from Long Island harvested oysters that are boiled in the brewing process, shell and all. Designed to be enjoyed with oysters raw or cooked, but approachable and encouraged to be enjoyed all occasions.

The British Mild is a session ale known for soft hop character and lower alcohol content. Flagship VAN DAM is black in color due to a complex malt profile. Using a wide variety of roasted, toasted, and caramel malts, this ale is bursting with dark beer character. The addition of Madagascar Bourbon vanilla blends a pleasant richness to the existing flavors. A medium but mellow body gives VAN DAM enjoyable drinkability during the winter months.

reviews.text:
For someone that really doesn't drink a lot of beer I go to a lot of beer events. Weird. So stop reading here if you love beer 'cause I can't review the beer. This is a review of the facilities.

There's a yard out back... I'm not expecting anything fancy, but they should have done it up a bit for their Oktoberfest. From my experience, balloons go a long way. Just a suggestion. Okay, I have a balloon fetish and I'll put balloons on everything if you let me. 

The tap room... Flies. So many flies. You know those restaurant grade bug zappers. It would be a good idea to get one. I was swatting at flies the entire time. 
The ac strip at the seating was a plus. Being able to charge your phone in any bar type establishment is always a good thing. 

I will review one drink they offer: the non-alcoholic Lemon Coffee Soda. SO bizarre upon the first sip, but it grows on you. Challenging enough for anyone who's a weirdo like me who doesn't like beer.

Final suggestion... if Bronx Brewery came out with a hard soda, I would be so on board with that. I recently had a hard kombucha that was beer like and absolutely delicious. Think about it Bronx Brewery. Think about it.

Good beer, friendly space to hang out. They have games available. Sometimes there are events in the brewery room (including yoga!) and outdoor seating is available in the summer. Kind of in a weird location, a bit of a walk from the 6 Train. But an easy bike ride from Astoria or Randall's Island.
Perfect ambiance and the beer tastes so Good! I'm happy my borough has a great place.

This place is great. This is what the South Bronx needs more of. Real businesses with real impacts on the area. The beer is great here, the atmosphere is really nice. Could stand to be a little bigger for more people to stop in. Dogs running around is awesome and makes the place feel relaxed. 

I really enjoy this place and it's doing great things to lift the area out of the dark ages. I hope they see nothing but great successes here.

Damian, the pups, and the rest of the crew were so welcoming. I came as a volunteer of an animal shelter that was invited to do an adoption event, and I'm already looking forward to returning soon. Such a great space and the beer is super tasty.
